-6,5,0,-1,15,12,32,37,20,26,37,12,15,16,48,-9,0,55,38,58,51,41]} 1. b3 {
This game started as Larsen opening, but soon trasposed into the English/
reversed Sicilian.} (1. c4 e5 {English opening with 1...e5 or reversed Sicilian
} 2. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Bd7d5] Our focus is on positions where Black plays ...d5,
which would correspond to White playing the open Sicilian (with d2-d4). We
will make comparisons to the Sicilian defense in places, to understand these
positions better - when an extra tempo matters and when it does not.} 3. Nf3
Nc6 {The position with 4 knights will be the focal point of our discussion.
White has many good options at this point, often trying to get the reversed
Sicilian with an extra tempo of his choice. We will discuss the reversed
Dragon:} 4. g3 ({reversed Scheveningen:} 4. d3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 ({and
Reversed Boleslavsky structure:} 6. e4)) ({and reversed Taimanov after} 4. a3)
4... d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 {etc.}) (1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 {Open Sicilian
- White plays similar variations with an extra tempo in the English opening.}
cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 {Accelerated Dragon} (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 e5 {[%csl Bd6,
Be5] Boleslavsky structure} (6... e6 {Scheveningen})) (4... e6 5. Nc3 Qc7 {
[%csl Bc7] Paulsen/Taimanov}) 5. Nc3 Bg7 {etc.}) 1... e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. c4 Nf6
4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {The main upsides of this structure for Black are free
piece play and good control of the centre. Potential downsides are exposed
e5-pawn and White's pressure along the c-file.} 6. a3 {White is going for the
flexible Paulsen/Kan approach with colours reversed.} Be6 7. Qc2 Bd6 {
Experience playing this position with colours reversed helps in comparing the
similarities/differences to the Sicilian Defense and choosing the appropriate
plan. Black's move is completely fine,} ({however,} 7... Qd7 $5 {would have
been even more ambitious, preparing queenside castling.} 8. Nf3 f6 {[%csl Bb3]
[%cal Bb3b4]} 9. b4 O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 10. Nc3 g5 {Black goes for the
English attack. This exact position appears often in the Taimanov Sicilian
with colours reversed. White has lost his extra tempo on b2-b3-b4.}) 8. Bb5 $6
{Keeping the pawn on d2 gives White flexibility regarding the development of
this bishop, but} ({it would have been better to go for the Scheveningen
scheme instead, by playing} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. b4 a6 10. d3 f5 11. Nbd2 {[%csl Bd2,
Bb2] White's opening move order allowed him also to be flexible with his
knight. Instead of c3, the knight can go to c4, from where it exerts pressure
on e5-pawn.} Qf6 12. Be2 Rae8 $13) 8... Nde7 (8... O-O $5 {was even more to
the point. Taking the pawn on c6 is too risky considering all the
light-squared weaknesses.}) 9. Nf3 a6 10. Bc4 Qd7 ({It would have been better
to keep the bishops on the board with} 10... Bf5 {and White could not exchange
them with} 11. Bd3 {due to the tactic} Bxa3 $1) 11. Bxe6 Qxe6 12. d3 {[#]
White's plan is to exchange the queens on c4-square. Should Black exchange the
queens, and if not, how should he avoid it?} Qg4 $2 (12... O-O 13. Nbd2 {
[%cal Gc2c4]}) (12... O-O-O $5 13. Qc4 Nd5 14. Nc3 Be7 $11) ({Perhaps the most
ambitious move is} 12... g5 $1 13. Qc4 Qg6 14. h3 O-O-O $132) (12... b5 $6 {
[%csl Rc6,Rc7]}) (12... Qg6 $5) 13. O-O Ng6 14. Nbd2 O-O 15. Qc4 Qxc4 16. Nxc4
Rad8 17. Rfd1 Rfe8 18. Kf1 f6 19. Ke2 {[#] We have a typical English endgame.
White prepares to put pressure on the c7-pawn by doubling up the rooks on the
c-file, pushing the b-pawn, etc. How should Black anticipate this plan?} Bf8 ({
The right idea is} 19... Nf8 $1 20. b4 Ne6 {[%csl Rc7] overprotecting the
c7-pawn with the knight. It is much better placed here than on g6, keeping
control over important squares like d4, c5, etc.}) (19... Rd7 {is fine, but
Black should manoeuvre the knight to e6 sooner or later, anyway.}) 20. Rac1 Kf7
21. b4 Rd7 22. Rc2 Red8 23. Ne1 Ke6 24. Rdc1 Kf7 25. g3 Be7 26. Nd2 Nf8 27. Nb3
Ne6 28. f4 exf4 29. gxf4 g6 30. Nf3 {[#] White is preparing the classical
exchange sacrifice on c6 - how would you respond as Black?} Rd5 $2 (30... Na7
$5 {removing the knight from c6 and preparing to solidify the structure with ..
.c6.} 31. d4 (31. Na5 c6 $11) 31... c6 32. Nc5 Bxc5 33. bxc5 Nc8 34. Rb1 Ne7
35. Bc1 Nf5 36. Rcb2 Re7 $1 $132) ({Black could also solve his problems in a
tactical way:} 30... Rxd3 $5 31. Nbd4 Ncxd4+ 32. Nxd4 R3xd4 33. Bxd4 Rxd4 (
33... Nxd4+ 34. exd4 c6 $11) 34. exd4 Nxd4+ 35. Kd3 Nxc2 36. Rxc2 Bd6 $11) 31.
d4 f5 $2 32. h4 h5 33. Rxc6 $1 {The classical exchange sacrifice comes at the
perfect moment. Black will be left with multiple pawn weaknesses and weak
squares.} bxc6 34. Rxc6 R8d6 35. Rc1 Bf6 36. Na5 Rb6 37. Nc4 Rb8 38. Nce5+ Kg7
39. Rg1 Nf8 40. Bc3 Rb6 41. Kd3 Bxe5 42. fxe5 Ne6 43. e4 fxe4+ 44. Kxe4 c6 45.
Bd2 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rg6] 1-0 (56) Black resigns.} 1-0

