the last move had created the additional threat Nxd5 followed by Bc3. Secondly,
after ...Nb6 followed by ...g5, the bishop will have to retreat in order to
clear the d2-square for the knight.} 13. b3 Bf6 14. Rab1 Qe7 $1 {[%csl Ba3]}
15. Bc1 Rad8 16. Na4 {[#] How should Black react to this move?} Nd7 $1 {
It is best to take c5-square under control to limit White's play on the
queenside.} (16... Nxa4 $6 17. bxa4 Bc8 18. Rb5 {[%cal Gc1b2]}) (16... g5 17.
Nc5 Bc8 18. b4 g4 19. Nd2 axb4 20. axb4 Qf7 21. b5 $36 {Bosboom,M (2385)
-Ermenkov,E (2475)/Amsterdam 1988/CBM 009 (1/2, 75)}) 17. Bb2 Qf7 18. Nd2 Qg6
$36 {[%cal Gf5f4]}) ({Another common approach with colours reversed is} 11.
Nxd5 Qxd5 {This is more flexible} ({than} 11... Bxd5 12. e4 Be6 13. exf5 Bxf5
14. Be3 $11) 12. Bd2 (12. e4 Qd6 {[%cal Ga8d8]}) 12... a4 13. Bc3 Bf6 $11) (11.
Bd2 {[#] How does Black typically reply to this move?} Nb6 $1 {[%csl Rd2][%cal
Rd2c3]} 12. Na4 Nxa4 13. Qxa4 Qd7 14. Qc2 Bf6 15. Rac1 Kh8 16. Bc3 {1/2-1/2 
(16) Johansen,D (2371)-Hague,B (2399) Tauranga 2020} a4 $11) (11. b3 $6 {
is problematic because of} Nxc3 12. Qxc3 e4 {[%csl Ra1,Rc3][%cal Ge7f6]}) 11...
Qd6 $146 {Preventing Nc5. The queen is slightly exposed, but in the game,
White did not find the best way to take advantage of this detail.} (11... Qe8
12. Bd2 {Rules should be approached with flexibility. In this concrete case,
delaying the thematic jump helps Black!} (12. Nc5 Bxc5 13. Qxc5 Qg6 14. d4 e4
15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 {looks like a better chance for some initiative.}) 12...
Qg6 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. Qxc5 e4 $1 {This is possible because Black had the time
to defend g5.} 15. Ne1 Ne5 16. f4 Nd7 17. Qc2 N7f6 18. dxe4 fxe4 19. Bc4 c6 $15
{[%csl Ge1] Nei,I (2200)-Tal,M (2615)/Moscow 1979/MCD (0-1, 37). Black has an
active position and is very stable on the light squares. Despite having the
better structure, White struggles to find a way of activating his knight.}) ({
The best move is, in fact:} 11... g5 $1 $36 {[%csl Ra4] taking advantage of
the fact that White does not have central counterplay with Nxd5 and e4.} 12. d4
(12. Nc5 $6 Bxc5 13. Qxc5 g4 14. Nd2 f4 $40) 12... e4 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 c6
15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Qxc5 Qe7 $15) 12. Rd1 {The most logical reaction. Black's
queen is almost caged in the centre and the opposition of the rook may become
profitable for White.} Rad8 {[#]} 13. d4 $6 {The course of the game strongly
suggests that this is not the best way to proceed.} ({White should have pushed
the other pawn instead:} 13. e4 Nf4 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Rac1 $132 {[%csl Rc7]}
Nd4 $1 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Qxc7 Bh4 18. Qxf4 Be7 $1 19. Nc3 fxe4 20. Qxe4 Qxf2+
21. Kh1 $11) (13. Nc3 $5 {also makes some sense, creating the threats Nb5 or
Ne4. It looks like a loss of time, but actually Black has committed himself
quite strongly with the last two moves. Once the queen's rook has departed
