-132]} 1. c4 (1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 {This is
the basic position of the Taimanov Sicilian.} 6. Be3 (6. Be2 a6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Be3) (6. Nxc6 {is not such a good move here.} bxc6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2
d5) 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bb7 12. Kb1
O-O {Black is typically doing well in practice.}) 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6
4. a3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qc2 {Flexible Paulsen/Taimanov approach} Nxc3 {
The most ambitious move. Black would like to play 7...Bd6.} (6... Be7 $5 {
is also a solid option, although I prefer developing the bishop to d6, if
possible.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bd3 Kh8 $1 {Not creating any weaknesses
