$11) (6... Be6 7. e3 Qd7 8. Be2 f6 9. b4 {White has an extra tempo compared to
the Sicilian Taimanov (see 1.e4). This tempo can mean a lot in positions with
opposite-side castling, so I would not recommend Black playing this way.}) 7.
bxc3 ({Recently some strong players have played} 7. dxc3 {preparing to play
e2-e4 in one go, which is usually not an option in the Taimanov Sicilian.
However, I think that this plan can be easily neutralized with} a5 8. e4 Bc5 9.
Bb5 (9. h3 O-O 10. Bb5 Qf6 11. Bg5 Qg6 12. g4 Be6 13. O-O-O f6 14. Be3 Bxe3+
15. fxe3 Qf7 $17 {1/2-1/2 (68) Vidit,S (2721) -Nakamura,H (2736) Moscow 2019})
(9. Bc4 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8f6,Gc8g4] is probably White's best, but Black
should have no problems in this type of position, anyway.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O
Qf6 11. Bg5 Qg6 12. Bxc6 $6 {weakening the light squares too much.} (12. Bh4)
12... bxc6 13. Bh4 f6 14. b4 Bb6 15. Bg3 Be6 16. Nh4 Qf7 $17 {0-1 (29)
Segerberg,T (1933) -Kuljasevic,D (2564) Rethymno 2012}) (7. Qxc3 $6 Qd6 {
[%cal Ge5e4]}) 7... Bd6 {[%csl Bd6]} 8. g3 {Again, using the fact that the
pawn is still on e2 to switch to a more flexible Dragon setup. This makes a
lot of sense considering that black has put his bishop on d6.} ({White could
also play} 8. e3 O-O 9. d4 {[%csl Ba3] A similar position is possible in the
Taimanov with colours reversed, but White has a useless move a2-a3, which
renders his extra tempo meaningless. Black has a comfortable position after}
Qe7 10. Be2 Bd7 11. O-O Rae8 12. Re1 b6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (48) Rosen,E (2338)
-Jacobson,A (2311) Saint Louis 2019}) 8... Qe7 9. d3 O-O 10. Bg2 Bd7 11. O-O
Rae8 12. e4 {[#] A sensible move to take space in the centre. Which plan
should Black choose now?} ({Another plan is} 12. Nd2 Na5 13. c4 f5 14. Bb2 b6 {
but Black is very solid, either way.}) 12... Na5 {preparing to play on the
queenside with ...c7-c5, etc. seems like the most promising choice.} (12... f5
{is tempting, but after} 13. exf5 (13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Qxb7 f4 $1 $36 {[%cal
Gg7g5,Gg5g4]}) 13... Bxf5 14. Nh4 Bc8 15. Be3 {White's control over e4-square
becomes an important factor in the position.} Kh8 16. Rfe1 Qf7 17. Nf3 Qg6 18.
Nd2 Bf5 19. Ne4 $14 {even though this kind of position is fairly balanced, it
seems easier to play with White due to the dominant knight.}) ({It also makes
sense to play} 12... Bc5 $5 13. Bb2 Qf6 $11 {[%cal Rd3d4,Gd7g4] keeping d3-d4
break under control.}) 13. Nh4 (13. d4 f6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd7e6] is a very
solid structure for Black. c4-square is a source of counterplay.}) (13. a4 c5)
13... b6 14. Nf5 Qf6 15. Ne3 ({Black does not mind the exchange on d6 as after
} 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. f4 f6 $132 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc7c5] he can generate good
counterplay against opponent's backward d-pawn.}) 15... Be6 16. Bb2 Bc5 {
[%cal Bf2f4,Bd3d4] A very important move, keeping both central breaks under
control.} 17. Qe2 Rd8 ({Perhaps it would have been even better to exchange the
other bishop for the knight by playing:} 17... Qd8 $5 18. Rad1 Bxe3 $1 19. Qxe3
Qd7 {[%cal Ge6h3,Ge8d8,Gc7c5]} 20. f4 $13) 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 Bd6 20. Rae1
Nb3 21. Qd1 Nc5 22. f4 $2 {A big positional mistake.} (22. c4 {would have kept
the position balanced.} Qg6 23. Re3 Nd7 24. d4 exd4 25. Bxd4 Rfe8 $11) 22...
exf4 23. d4 Nd7 24. gxf4 Qh4 25. Re5 Nf6 26. Qe1 Qxe1 27. Rexe1 Rfe8 $17 {
White pawn structure is in ruins.} 28. Bc1 b5 $1 29. Bd2 Bxa3 30. Rb1 a6 31.
Bf3 Nxd5 $19 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

