[White "Structures with dxc3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/ppp2ppp/3p4/4p3/2P5/2P3P1/PP2PP1P/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[EventDate "2019.06.04"]

{[#]This is the second typical structure you should know. In comparison to
structure 1, here White has less central control. On the other hand, he can
make use of the semi-open d-file and especially d5-square. After installing a
knight on d5, White usually starts gaining space on the kingside. When allowed,
c4-c5 can be an idea in this structure as well. Just like in the structures
with bxc3, Black should try to execute his light-squared strategy. While the
breaks ...f7-f5 and ...d6-d5 remain valid, in this structure the break ...
b7-b5 is much more common than in the structures with bxc3. This idea works
extremely well when White has played e2-e4 before Black's ...Nc6. In such a
case Black usually plays ...Nbd7 followed by ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5. This
knight usually lands on the c5-square. Even though some exceptions are dealt
with, in the setups with ...Nc6, Black usually plays for ...f7-f5. Practice
shows that in positions where White has played e2-e4 and f2-f3, Black is
advised to open the position with ...c7-c6 followed by ...d6-d5. In the
arising open position, the vulnerable white king is more important than the
bishop pair.}  *

