{[%evp 0,77,27,-22,-15,-15,21,-6,11,11,16,20,21,22,29,-5,8,27,38,35,60,21,40,
74,60,61,56,55,96,101,112,130,152,103,95,76,70,71,78,69,88,70,79,78,104,92,97,
93,97,103,107,121,147,132,133,137,121,121,121,126,118,118,122,139,147,147,153,
189,189,199,926,1290,1290,1718,29989,29990,29991,1415,1562,1602] We starts
with a game which is a perfect illustration of White's ideas in the structure
arising after bxc3.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 {The system with 2...Bb4 is the most
straightforward approach for those who want to play against doubled pawns. In
this lecture, I will try to prove that this line is perfectly playable from a
theoretical point of view.} 3. g3 Bxc3 4. bxc3 d6 5. Bg2 Ne7 {The knight is
quite flexible on e7. Black leaves the way of the f-pawn open so that Black
could play ...f7-f5 or ...f7-f6, if needed.} 6. d3 O-O 7. Nh3 {Putting the
knight on h3 is White's most logical approach. As pointed out in the
introduction, gaining space on the kingside is White's main positional idea in
such structures. With a knight on h3, White can easily carry out the advance
f2-f4.} Nbc6 {Even though this is not a mistake, I believe Black should avoid
blocking the c-pawn.} ({More to the point is} 7... c5 {as we will see in the
next examples.}) 8. O-O Bg4 $2 {This is already a mistake. Besides preventing
e2-e4, Black is planning to harass the h3-knight with ...Qd7. White, however,
can play the simple} 9. f3 {when it turns out that Black's last move is just a
waste of time.} Bh5 $2 {The bishop has nothing to do on h5. As the game shows,
White can win a tempo by means of the generally useful g3-g4 advance.} 10. e4 {
This thematic move cannot be a bad idea. Before proceeding with his kingside
play, White gains space in the centre.} ({Another interesting option would
have been} 10. g4 Bg6 11. f4 exf4 12. Nxf4 {[%cal Ge2e4] White managed to
create an annoying pressure due to the strong central control and bishop pair.}
) 10... Qd7 11. g4 Bg6 12. Rb1 $1 {A very thematic move for this pawn
structure. Seemingly, White is trying to put pressure on b7. Nevertheless, the
deep idea behind this little move is swinging the rook to the kingside via the
second rank. Such ideas illustrate the modern understanding of the doubled
pawns. Even though doubled pawns are weak in the long run, they provide
semi-open files which allow early activation of the major pieces. This
tendency of preferring positions with doubled pawns is visible in the games of
the World Champion Magnus Carlsen as well.} b6 13. f4 f6 $6 {The f6-pawn will
be a hook for White's kingside play. Nevertheless, Black cannot do without
this move.} ({Slightly better would have been} 13... exf4 {preventing White
from gaining even more space with f4-f5. Even in this case, however, after} 14.
Nxf4 f6 15. h4 Bf7 16. Bh3 Be6 17. Rb2 Ne5 18. Rg2 $40 {White has decent
attacking chances.}) 14. f5 Bf7 15. g5 {Now, White's attack plays itself.
Black has no counterplay whatsoever. Therefore, Plachetka just starts bringing
all his pieces to the kingside.} Kh8 16. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1h4]} fxg5 17. Nxg5 Ng8
18. Qh4 Nf6 19. Rb2 $1 {[%cal Gg2h3,Gb2g2] Finally, the rook joins the attack.
White is planning Bh3 followed by Rg2.} Rae8 20. Bh3 Nd8 21. Rg2 Bg8 22. Kh1 {
[%cal Gf1g1]} Re7 23. Rfg1 Qe8 24. Bg4 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gg4d1] The bishop will
be ideally placed on d1. In this way, besides being ready to join the attack
via h5, the bishop will not interfere with the other white pieces.} c5 25. Bd1
a6 26. a4 {This move is a bit overcautious. In any case, White is completely
winning since the kingside attack is unstoppable.} ({Just enough would have
been} 26. Qh3 {[%cal Gg5f3,Gf3h4,Gh4g6] preparing the transfer of the knight
to g6.}) 26... b5 27. axb5 axb5 28. cxb5 Qxb5 29. c4 Qb8 30. Nf3 Nc6 31. Qh3 h6
32. Ba4 Nb4 33. Rxg7 Rxg7 34. Rxg7 Kxg7 35. Qxh6+ Kf7 36. Bg5 Bh7 37. Bxf6 Rg8
38. Ng5+ Rxg5 39. Bxg5 1-0

