{The next example is quite similar to the first one. This time, however, the
position is more complicated since Black meets f2-f4 with ...exf4, not
allowing his opponent to gain space with f4-f5. The first 8 moves repeat the
previous game.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3 4. bxc3 d6 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. d3 O-O
7. Nh3 Nbc6 8. O-O h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7] By taking the g5-square
away from the knight, Black prepares the typical ...Be6 followed by ...Qd7. On
the other hand, the h6-pawn can often become a target.} ({I believe it is
better the prepare the same idea with} 8... f6) 9. f4 Be6 10. e4 {[%cal Gf4f5]
White is already threatening f4-f5. Therefore, Black should react immediately -
} exf4 11. Nxf4 Qd7 12. Rb1 $1 {[%cal Gb1b2,Gb2f2] Once again, we can see the
same idea. White is planning to transfer his rook to f2. The compact pawn
centre, bishop pair, and the semi-open f-file provide an advantage for White.
A typical way of increasing the kingside pressure in such positions is h2-h3
followed by g3-g4 and Nh5.} Rab8 13. Rb2 $1 Ne5 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black's only
counterplay is based on the advance ...b7-b5. Therefore, Kovalenko settled for
the prophylactic} 14. a4 ({It turns out, however, that White can just focus on
his kingside play which is pretty dangerous. Better would have been} 14. h3 {
when after} b5 $6 ({Better is} 14... f6 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Rbf2 $14 {with a
slight advantage for White.}) {White can opt for the following sequence:} 15.
cxb5 Rxb5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rxf8+ Kxf8 18. Rf2+ Kg8 19. d4 $18 {White has a
winning position due to 3 main factors: 1) weak black king 2) strong centre 3)
powerful bishop pair}) 14... Bg4 15. Qc2 N5g6 16. Be3 b6 17. Qb3 {White clears
the second rank for the rook and prepares Qb5 in a suitable moment.} ({
Nevertheless, more energetic would have been} 17. h3 {when after} Nxf4 ({After
} 17... Be6 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. d4 $14 {White enjoys a stable advantage.}) 18.
gxf4 Bxh3 19. f5 $44 {White has a tremendous compensation for the pawn.}) 17...
a5 (17... Kh8 18. h3 Nxf4 19. gxf4 Bxh3 20. f5 Bxg2 21. Rxg2 f6 $13) 18. h3 Be6
$6 {Black plays into White's hand.} ({He should have accepted the pawn
sacrifice after} 18... Nxf4 19. gxf4 Bxh3 20. f5 Bg4 21. Rbf2 $44 {Even though
White has an obvious compensation, there is a lot of fight left in the
position.}) 19. d4 Qc8 20. Kh2 Kh7 21. Nxe6 Qxe6 22. Rbf2 {Finally, the rook
occupies its perfect spot. Black's position is already very difficult.} Rbe8
23. Qb5 Ng8 24. Bd2 Nf6 $2 {Serious mistake in a difficult position. White is
winning on the spot.} 25. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 26. Qh5 Rh8 27. e5 {Black resigned.} 1-0

