{[%evp 0,88,23,-18,-21,-21,39,-9,14,8,10,20,28,9,12,5,31,32,25,24,40,41,36,38,
36,40,40,29,31,39,24,13,9,-10,-7,11,9,3,-2,-19,-7,-6,-7,-24,-12,-60,-49,-83,
-77,-81,-92,-95,-68,-46,-70,-75,-62,-47,-75,-88,-69,-166,-213,-142,-180,-196,
-196,-221,-217,-226,-155,-195,-191,-181,-121,-161,-146,-157,-177,-155,-203,
-216,-210,-267,-343,-226,-424,-460,-207,-1299,-916] Now, we shall take a look
at how Black must fight against White's setup from the first two examples. The
first 7 moves repeat the previous games:} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3 4.
bxc3 d6 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. d3 O-O 7. Nh3 c5 $1 {To my understanding, this is
Black's optimal setup. Of course, after parting with the dark-squared bishop,
it's normal to put the pawns on dark squares. Besides that, by playing ...
c7-c5, Black gains space.} 8. O-O Nbc6 9. Rb1 b6 10. f4 {Kovalenko is going
for his favourite kingside strategy.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gd8d7] With a pawn on f4 
(instead of f2), this move is very precise. In order to rule out any Ng5-based
ideas, before putting the bishop on e6, Black is forcing the white knight into
the slightly passive f2-square.} 11. Nf2 Be6 12. e4 {[%cal Gf4f5] White is now
ready to play the thematic f4-f5. Therefore, Black should react immediately.}
exf4 $1 {Remember this thematic idea. In such structures, the best defence
against f4-f5 is taking on f4 followed by ...f7-f5, if White recaptures with a
pawn.} 13. Bxf4 {Taking with the bishop is more logical. If allowed, White
will try to make use of the f-file and the f5-outpost. In an ideal world, he
would play h2-h3 followed by g3-g4. Afterwards, it's possible to manoeuvre the
knight to f5 and double the rooks on the f-file. Nevertheless, taking with a
piece on f4 has one serious drawback - Black can occupy the e5-square with a
knight.} ({Of course,} 13. gxf4 {is well met by} f5 $15 {[%csl Re4,Rf4][%cal
Gd8d7,Ga8e8] Black is planning to follow with ...Qd7 and ...Rae8, thus putting
a lot of pressure on f4 and e4. Very often, after making all the necessary
preparations, Black can destroy White's centre with ...fxe4.}) 13... Qd7 14.
Qc2 Ng6 15. Bd2 Nge5 {Black managed to establish a powerful knight on e5. Now,
he can consider the execution of his light-square strategy. In order to do so,
he will prepare the advance ...f7-f5. Afterwards, in order to fight for the
light squares, Black will try to exchange the light-squared bishops as well as
a pair of knights. The perfect configuration would be queen and knight against
queen and dark-squared bishop. In such a case, Black will enjoy complete
domination on the light squares.} 16. Rbe1 Rae8 17. Bf4 Ng6 18. Bc1 h6 19. h3
Kh8 {By removing the king from the diagonal a2-g8, Black indicates his
intention to prepare ...f7-f5.} 20. Kh2 Nce5 21. Nd1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gd1e3,
Ge3f5] As pointed out earlier, bringing the knight to f5 is an important part
of White's plan. Therefore, Black played} f5 $1 {Just in time! Black's pieces
are ready for the opening of the position.} 22. d4 $2 {It's difficult to
explain this decision. White just loses the c4-pawn without any compensation.}
({More tenacious would have been} 22. exf5 Rxf5 23. Rxf5 Bxf5 24. Re3 {Black
is slightly better but White holds.}) 22... Nxc4 $17 23. Qd3 b5 24. h4 fxe4 25.
Bxe4 Ne7 26. Rxf8+ Rxf8 27. dxc5 dxc5 28. Qxd7 Bxd7 29. Ne3 Ne5 30. Ba3 b4 31.
cxb4 Rf2+ 32. Kg1 Rxa2 33. Bc1 cxb4 34. Nd5 N7c6 35. Bf4 b3 36. Nc3 Ra5 37. Rf1
g5 38. hxg5 hxg5 39. Bc1 Nc4 40. Rf7 N6e5 41. Re7 Ra1 42. Nb1 Bc6 43. Bf5 Nd6
44. Be4 Bxe4 0-1

