{Let's take a look at another example featuring the idea ... exf4 followed by .
..f7-f5. This time, White recaptures with the g-pawn and later takes on f5. He
tries to compensate the inferior pawn structure with a dynamic play. As we are
going to witness, this approach didn't work out.} 9... f6 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7]
As I mentiond in my comments to the first example, ... f7-f6 is a better way
of preparing ...Be6 and ...Qd7 than ...h7-h6.} 10. e4 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gf2f4]
White is planning Nh4 followed by f2-f4. Black is just in time to carry out
his thematic response.} Be6 11. Nh4 Qd7 12. f4 exf4 13. gxf4 f5 $1 {White
should now take a difficult decision. Black is planning to proceed with ...
fxe4, thus obtaining a superior pawn structure since White cannot recapture
with the d-pawn. Therefore, Dautov decides to force matters in order to get a
dynamic compensation for his spoiled pawn structure.} 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Nxf5
Bxf5 16. Qf3 $2 {This move is already a huge mistake.} ({Better was} 16. Bd5+
Be6 17. Qg4 {Nevertheless, Black has an elegant solution at his disposal -}
Rae8 18. Re1 Bxd5 $1 19. Qxd7 Rxe1+ 20. Kf2 Re7 21. Qh3 Be6 22. Qg3 Rf6 $15 {
[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc6e5,Ge7f7] with more than enough compensation. White has a
vulnerable king and inferior pawn structure.}) ({Immediately loses} 16. Qa4 $2
{due to} Bxd3 $1 17. Rb2 (17. Bxc6 Qg4+ $19) 17... Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Ne5 $19) 16...
Ne7 17. Bd2 Rae8 {[%cal Ge7g6] Black has a huge advantage. There is no
activity left to compensate White for the damaged pawn structure.} 18. Rbe1 Ng6
19. d4 Nh4 20. Qc6 Nxg2 21. Qxd7 Bxd7 22. Kxg2 Be6 23. c5 Bxa2 $19 {Black is
already winning.} 24. Re3 Rxe3 25. Bxe3 a5 26. Ra1 Bb3 27. Re1 Re8 28. Kf2 Kf7
29. cxb6 cxb6 30. Bc1 Rxe1 31. Kxe1 Ke6 32. Ba3 Kd5 33. Kd2 b5 34. Kd3 Bd1 35.
Kd2 Bg4 36. Kc2 Bh3 37. Kb3 h5 38. Kc2 Bf5+ 39. Kb3 h4 40. Bc1 Ke4 41. Bd2 d5
42. Be1 h3 43. Bg3 Ke3 44. Ka3 Bg6 45. Kb3 Bd3 46. Ka3 Bc4 47. Kb2 a4 48. Ka3
Kd2 49. Kb2 a3+ 50. Kxa3 Kxc3 51. Be1+ Kxd4 52. Bf2+ Ke4 53. Kb4 d4 0-1

