{In many cases, the advance c4-c5 creates practical problems for Black. The
explanation is simple. Black players are not always ready to face a drastic
change in the nature of the position. Let's take a look at a typical example.
In this position, White played} 10. c5 $5 dxc5 11. Be3 Qe7 {So far so good.
Even though Black managed to bring a dynamic potential to the position, he
still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn. In the game, Gyula Pap
followed with the creative} 12. Rxb7 Bxb7 13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Qxb7 Qd6 $2 {
White's dynamic play actually paid off. After this serious mistake, Black's
position is getting almost lost.} ({More precise would have been} 14... Qd7 $1
{when after} 15. Nd2 Nd5 16. Bxc5 Rab8 17. Qa6 Rfe8 18. c4 Nb6 19. e3 $44 {
White has compensation for the exchange but nothing more.}) 15. Ng5 $1 {
[%csl Ra8][%cal Gg5f7] This is the point! Black cannot deal with White's
multiple threats.} Rab8 $2 {After this move, the game is over.} ({More
tenacious would have been} 15... e4 $8 16. Qxa8 Rxa8 17. Nf7+ Kg8 18. Nxd6 cxd6
19. Rd1 $16 {Despite White's obvious advantage, Black can still put up some
fight.}) 16. Qxc6 $18 Rb2 17. Bxc5 Qxc6 18. Bxc6 Rc8 19. Nf7+ Kg8 20. Nxe5 Rxe2
21. d4 g6 22. Bb5 Rb2 23. Nc6 Kg7 24. Nxa7 Rb8 25. a4 Ne4 26. Nc6 Ra8 27. c4
Nd2 28. d5 Rc2 29. Nb4 Nf3+ 30. Kg2 Rc3 31. Be3 Rb3 32. Kxf3 Rxb4 33. Ra1 1-0

