{[%evp 0,72,19,-22,-15,-15,18,-15,10,10,18,11,61,59,101,45,21,6,3,-9,16,7,33,
13,-10,5,-16,-45,-14,-37,-41,-41,-19,-52,-61,-45,-76,-80,-80,-174,-133,-161,
-163,-145,-147,-135,-116,-121,-140,-429,-95,-170,-524,-567,-557,-591,-221,-221,
-305,-294,-334,-334,-350,-350,-358,-358,-358,-559,-582,-582,-605,-596,-537,
-535,-618] Now, we are going to see an example which shows how to put pressure
on the c4-pawn. Such a scenario can occur when White has already committed to
d2-d4. The following game is very instructive.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3
4. bxc3 d6 5. Bg2 f5 {This is an ambitious approach to the opening. Black
immediately seizes space on the kingside. On the other hand, in some cases,
Black's position might prove a bit overextended.} 6. d4 {This move implies a
strategical risk. Even though White starts an immediate fight for the centre,
in many cases, the c4-pawn might become vulnerable.} ({More common is} 6. d3 {
which leads to a complex strategical battle.}) 6... Nc6 $2 {[%csl Rc4][%cal
Gc6a5] Razuvaev immediately tries to make use of the drawbacks of White's last
move. The knight is now ready to put pressure on c4 via the a5-square. The
immediate 6...Nc6, however, does not work tactically.} ({Black should have
started with} 6... Nf6) ({or} 6... Qe7 {The move ...Nc6 should have been
played a bit later.}) 7. Nf3 $2 {White misses his chance, thus justifying
Black's idea.} ({After} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nf3 e4 11.
Ne5 $16 {White enjoys a huge advantage.}) 7... e4 8. Ng5 Nf6 {[%csl Rc4,Ge4]
[%cal Gc6a5] Structurally speaking, Black is already better. The e4-pawn gives
a lot of space and restricts the white pieces. Therefore, White's main idea in
this structure is to challenge Black's pawn centre by means of f2-f3. In
general, if Black manages to hold his e4-pawn, he will be better since the
weakness on c4 will tell.} 9. f3 h6 10. Nh3 O-O 11. O-O Na5 {[%csl Rc4] Given
the fact that the e4-pawn is safely protected, Black can proceed with his
typical queenside play.} 12. fxe4 fxe4 13. Nf2 Bf5 14. c5 {White is trying to
bring some dynamics to the position. Black has many ways to deal with this
advance but Razuvaev went for the most precise reaction -} Qd7 {This is a
multi-functional move. Black connects the rooks, takes the a4-square for the
white queen, and protects the bishop. When your opponent has already committed
to c4-c5, you should encourage him to proceed with cxd6. As a result of the
pawn exchanges, Black will put pressure against the backward c3-pawn.} 15. cxd6
cxd6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c3] Black's position is structurally winning.
White has no counterplay whatsoever.} 16. d5 Rac8 17. Qd4 Rc4 $1 {Another
precise move that practically decides the game. The point is that} 18. Qxa7 {
is met by} Ra4 {After} 19. Bd2 Nb3 $19 {Black was completely winning.} 20. axb3
Rxa7 21. Rxa7 Qb5 22. Be3 Qxe2 23. Bd4 e3 24. Nd1 Be4 25. Nxe3 Ng4 26. Rxf8+
Kxf8 27. Ra1 Qb2 28. Rf1+ Kg8 29. Rf4 Nxe3 30. Bxe4 Qc1+ 31. Kf2 Qd2+ 32. Kf3
Ng2 33. Rf5 Ne1+ 34. Kg4 Qe2+ 35. Bf3 Nxf3 36. Rxf3 h5+ 0-1

