{Sometimes, by creating a pawn contact with one of the doubled pawns, we can
activate our pieces. With doubled pawns on c3 and c4, such a pawn break would
be ...d7-d5. In order to avoid the spoiling of his own pawn structure after ...
dxc4, White should play cxd5 which allows ...Qxd5 followed by swinging the
queen to the kingside. Let's take a look at one model game by GM Ivan Sokolov.
} 1. c4 ({With colours reversed, the same idea can be seen in the Rossolimo
Sicilian -} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. O-O Bg7 6. Re1 Nf6 7.
e5 Nd5 8. c4 Nc7 9. d4 $1 {This energetic pawn break allows White to bring his
queen to h4.} cxd4 10. Qxd4 Ne6 11. Qh4 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gb1c3,Gc3e4] with good
attacking chances.}) 1... e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. g3 Bxc3 4. bxc3 Nf6 5. Bg2 O-O 6.
Nf3 Re8 7. O-O e4 {The advance ...e5-e4 is a typical way of gaining space in
the structures with bxc3. Of course, such an advanced pawn requires energetic
play. Otherwise, after removing the knight, White will challenge the centre by
means of f2-f3.} 8. Ne1 ({After} 8. Nd4 c5 9. Nc2 d5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 {we get the
Rossolimo position with colours reversed. The ideas are similar to the game.})
8... Nc6 {This move is slightly dubious in view of the game continuation.} 9.
d3 ({A more common way of attacking the centre is} 9. f3 exf3 10. Nxf3 {
White hopes that his good central control, bishop pair, and semi-open f-file
will compensate for the inferior pawn structure. An important position arises
after} Qe7 11. e3 Ne5 12. Nd4 d6 13. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gc1g5,Gd4f5] White is
ready to mount the pressure by means of e3-e4 followed by Bg5 and Nf5. Black,
however, can apply his light square strategy in a very instructive way -} c5 $1
14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. Rxf5 d5 $1 16. cxd5 c4 $1 {This is the point. As compensation
for the pawn, Black gets control of the weak light squares in the centre.} 17.
dxc4 ({After} 17. d4 Nd3 $132 {The powerful knight and the weak e4-square
provides Black with more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. He is
ready to follow with ...Ne4.0-1 (40) Khismatullin, D (2642)-Tomashevsky, E 
(2747) Chita 2015}) 17... Nxc4 18. Qd3 Rac8 {0-1 (69) Ghosh,D (2550)-Gupta,A 
(2603) New Delhi 2020. Black's position should be preferred due to his better
pawn structure and safer king.}) 9... d5 $1 {This typical idea allows Black to
activate the queen.} 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc2 Qh5 {[%cal Gc8h3] Mission completed.
Black is now preparing ...Bh3. As we know, his light square strategy includes
exchanging of the light-squared bishops as well as a pair of knights.} 12. Ne3
({Another game saw} 12. dxe4 $6 Nxe4 13. Bb2 Bh3 14. Ne3 $2 Rad8 $19 {with a
winning position for Black. 0-1 (26) Pantzar,M (2421)-Eljanov,P (2672) Chess.
com INT 2021}) 12... Bh3 13. d4 Rad8 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ge5g4,Gd8d1] by creating an
opposition with the queen, Black introduces the threat of ...Nc6-e5-g4, thus
exchanging the e3-knight.} 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qa4 Na5 {This is the positional
approach. Sokolov takes the control of the c4-square.} ({More aggressive would
have been} 15... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5] with the idea of ...Ned5. A possible line
would be} 16. Rb2 Ned5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. c4 Nf6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d4,Gf6g4,
Gh3g2] when Black is better.}) 16. Qb5 $6 {The endgame will be favourable for
Black due to his better pawn structure.} ({White should have settled for the
dynamic} 16. Bxh3 Qxh3 17. c4 Ng4 (17... Rxd4 $6 18. Bb2 $13) ({An interesting
idea would be} 17... h5 $5) 18. Nxg4 Qxg4 19. Bd2 Qxe2 20. Bxa5 bxa5 21. Rfe1 {
with roughly equal position.}) 16... Qxb5 17. Rxb5 {Even though this move
introduces a nice positional idea, I think that this is not the most precise
continuation.} Bxg2 (17... Be6 18. Rb2 c6 {[%cal Gb6b5] followed by ...b6-b5
would have provided Black with a huge advantage due to the domination on the
light squares.}) 18. Kxg2 c6 19. Rb1 $2 {This calculation mistake allows Black
to obtain a decisive positional advantage.} ({More tenacious would have been} 
19. Rb2 Nd5 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gd5e3,Ga5c4] when White has enough time to play} 20.
a4 {keeping drawing chances. In comparison with 19.Rb1, now taking the pawn
with} Nxc3 {is not dangerous since the rook is not hanging. White can just play
} 21. Bd2 Nxa4 22. Rb4 Nc5 23. dxc5 Rxd2 24. cxb6 axb6 25. Rxb6 $11 {[%csl Ra5]
with equality.}) 19... Nd5 $1 20. Bd2 Nxe3+ 21. Bxe3 Nc4 22. a4 a5 23. Rb3 Rd5
$19 {Black is strategically winning due to his better structure and domination
on the light squares. I provide the remaining part of the game without
annotations.} 24. Rfb1 Rb8 25. Bf4 Rb7 26. f3 e3 27. g4 f6 28. h4 h6 29. h5 Kf7
30. Rd1 Re7 31. Rdb1 Rb7 32. Rd1 Ke8 33. Kg3 Kd8 34. Rd3 Re7 35. Bxe3 Rxe3 36.
Rxe3 Nxe3 37. Rxb6 Kc7 38. Rb3 Rd8 39. Kf2 Nc4 40. e4 Rb8 41. Rxb8 Kxb8 42. f4
Nb2 43. e5 fxe5 44. dxe5 Nxa4 45. g5 Nxc3 46. f5 Ne4+ 47. Ke3 Nxg5 48. Kd4 0-1

