{[%evp 0,42,34,-16,-2,-3,-22,-23,-22,-29,-13,-65,-15,-9,7,2,29,24,34,38,17,14,
17,17,25,10,41,33,42,42,86,53,-8,-96,-108,-181,-177,-225,-228,-193,-226,-593,
-280,-295,-262] Finally, we are going to take a look at an example in which
Black strikes in the centre by means of ...c7-c6 followed by ...d7-d5. This
strategy works well when White goes for an early e2-e4.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3.
g3 Bb4 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e4 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d3,Gf2f4] White prepares Nge2
followed by d2-d3, 0-0 and f2-f4. In such a case, he would develop a serious
kingside initiative due to the better control of the centre. Black, however,
has a strong antidote to this plan -} Bxc3 6. bxc3 {Preparing ...c7-c6
followed by ...d7-d5.} Re8 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7d5]} ({The immediate} 6... c6 {
was possible as well. A possible continuation would be} 7. Ne2 d5 8. cxd5 cxd5
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. O-O Nc6 11. Rb1 Nb6 12. d4 Be6 $132 {Black's compact pawn
structure and control of the light squares are more than enough compensation
for the bishop pair.}) 7. d3 $6 {In my opinion, this move is less flexible. In
many cases, White would play d2-d4 at once.} ({More common is} 7. Ne2 {Of
course, Black will follow the same strategy -} c6 8. O-O d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10.
exd5 Nxd5 11. Rb1 Nc6 {This is one of the main tabiyas of the variation. I
believe that Black has a comfortable play in such structures. Playing on the
light squares and putting pressure along the d-file is the best strategy in
such structures. Black might follow with natural moves such as ...Nb6, ...Bf5,
...Qd7, and ...Rad8.}) 7... c6 8. Ne2 d5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Rb1 Nc6
12. O-O Bg4 $1 {This is the most precise continuation. The c3-pawn is
currently hanging. We can now see the drawback of playing the early d2-d3.} 13.
f3 Bf5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd5b6] This is the more ambitious approach. Black's
idea is to increase the pressure on d3 by playing ...Nb6.} ({A solid option
would have been} 13... Be6) {This is forced. Otherwise, White's position is
falling apart.} 14. Rxb7 Nb6 15. f4 e4 16. Qb3 $2 {After this mistake, White's
position is completely lost.} ({Topalov should have chosen} 16. dxe4 Bxe4 17.
Qb3 (17. Bxe4 Rxe4 $19 {[%csl Rb7,Re2]}) 17... Qf6 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Nd4 Na5
20. Qc2 Rxd4 21. Rxb6 axb6 22. cxd4 Qxd4+ 23. Qf2 $11 {Even though Black's
play remains slightly easier, objectively speaking, the position is equal.})
16... Be6 $1 $19 17. Qb5 exd3 18. Rxb6 dxe2 19. Re1 Bc4 20. Qxc6 Qd1 21. Kf2
Rad8 0-1

