{[%evp 0,42,35,-26,-3,-26,-25,-33,-17,-17,11,-20,-22,-15,-8,-17,-10,-30,-17,
-30,-34,-29,-23,-18,-16,-2,2,4,17,5,7,0,-3,-3,15,-16,6,0,28,12,12,4,-29,-80,
-135] After studying the most important ideas in the structure with bxc3, we
shall now look at the positions arising after dxc3. In the first example,
Anish Giri (playing with Black) demonstrated Black's model setup against one
of the most popular systems.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 Bb4 4. Nf3 Bxc3 5. dxc3
d6 6. Bg2 {Since the pawn structure is already clarified, we can remind the
plans of both players. White's plan is usually based on the knight transfer to
d5. This manoeuvre can be done via two alternative routes: 1) Nd2-f1-e3-d5 2)
Ne1-c2-e3-d5 After installing a knight on d5 and seizing space in the centre
with e2-e4. In the other hand, as we already know, Black should try to apply
his usual light square strategy. Therefore, he will try to exchange the
light-squared bishops as well as a pair of knights. Depending on the concrete
circumstances, Black will execute one of the following pawn breaks: 1) ...
f7-f5 2) ...d6-d5 3) ...b7-b5 In the following examples, I am going to explain
when is the optimal moment for each one of these pawn breaks.} h6 {This move
is quite typical for such structures. By taking the control of the g5-square,
Black is planning to proceed with ...Be6 followed by ...Qd7, thus preparing
the exchange of the bishops via h3.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is a
typical way to prepare the advance e2-e4. The next few moves are quite logical
-} Be6 9. b3 Qd7 10. e4 Bh3 11. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1g2,Gg2e3,Ge3d5]} O-O 12. f3 Nh7
$1 {[%cal Gh3g2,Gf7f5,Gf8f7,Ga8f8,Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Gh7g5,Ge6g5] A typical way of
preparing the advance ...f7-f5. Since ...d7-d5 and ...b7-b5 breaks are not
possible, ...f7-f5 is Black's only constructive idea. The knight is very well
placed on h7. After exchanging the bishops and playing ...f7-f5, Black can get
one of his knights to the ideal g5-square. This idea could be prepared by
means of the manoeuvre...Nc6-d8-e6. Of course, Black will double his rooks on
the f-file as well.} 13. Be3 {[%cal Gc4c5]} b6 $1 {Remember this little pawn
move. Whenever White is ready to execute the advance c4-c5, you should be
ready to play this move.} 14. Rd1 Bxg2 {It is instructive to see how Giri
waited with this exchange until White committed to Be3. Now, the bishop stands
on the way of the knight to d5-square.} 15. Nxg2 f5 16. exf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Rf3]
[%cal Ga8f8,Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Gh7g5]} 17. f4 exf4 18. Nxf4 Ne7 $6 {I find this move
a bit passive.} ({More to the point would have been} 18... Ne5 {heading to
f3-square.}) 19. Qe4 $6 {The centralization of the queen is premature. Black
would like to play ...Re8 in any case.} ({More reliable was} 19. Qd3 {with a
balanced position.}) 19... Re8 $15 20. Qb7 $4 {This move is losing on the spot.
} Nc6 $1 $19 21. Nd5 Rxd5 0-1

