{[%evp 0,68,19,-2,-14,-12,16,-22,-2,5,5,6,15,23,32,18,17,20,19,31,19,-14,-1,
-14,-7,-17,14,-35,-10,-121,-121,-125,-125,-125,-125,-125,-124,-134,-133,-133,
-141,-146,-138,-145,-142,-142,-142,-149,-164,-162,-145,-159,-156,-156,-116,
-212,-208,-206,-206,-161,-175,-165,-165,-166,-171,-171,-175,-173,-175,-273,
-267] The next fragment is taken from the practice of my trainer GM Viktor
Gavrikov who was a great expert in such structures. This game deals with the
advance ...b7-b5. After the normal moves} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. Bg2
Bxc3 5. dxc3 d6 {White played} 6. e4 $6 {which is already a dubious move. At
this point, you should remember a very important rule. In general, White is
not advised to play e2-e4 before Black's ...Nc6. In the game, Gavrikov shows
the reason. He went for the precise} Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,
Gc8b7,Gd7c5,Gb7e4,Gc5e4,Gf6e4] With the long diagonal being closed by the
advance e2-e4, Black can start preparing ...b7-b5. His next moves will be ...
a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7. In such a scenario, the knight belongs
to the c5-square. Therefore, Gavrikov starts with 6...Nbd7.} 7. Ne2 a6 $5 8.
O-O ({Preventing ...b7-b5 with} 8. a4 {has drawbacks as well. In this case,
Black should change his setup a bit. It's important to provoke b2-b3 by playing
} Nc5 9. f3 Be6 10. b3 {Having a knight on c5, Black can make use of the
vulnerable b3-pawn with the thematic} b5 $1 {The game might continue} 11. axb5
axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. b4 Na4 14. cxb5 Bc4 15. Qc2 Bxb5 $15 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3,Re2]
[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6f1] with ...Qa6 to follow. Black has an excellent play on the
weakened light squares.}) 8... b5 9. cxb5 axb5 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ga8a2,Gc8b7,
Gd7c5] This pawn modification is always favourable for Black. He can now
combine the pressure along the a-file with the attack on e4.} 10. Be3 Bb7 {
Provoking f2-f3 is an important part of Black's strategy. This move weakens
the king as well as the e3-square. Therefore, under favourable circumstances,
Black can open the position by executing the advance ...d6-d5.} 11. f3 O-O 12.
a4 bxa4 13. Rxa4 Bc6 $1 {Important little move. Gavrikov wants to exchange the
rooks on his terms.} 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. b4 $6 {This antipositional move further
weakens the light squares.} ({Probably White should have settled for the
passive but solid} 15. Nc1 {Nevertheless, after} Rb8 16. Qc2 d5 {Black's has
an edge.}) 15... Bb5 {Black immediately takes advantage of the newly weakened
light squares.} 16. Qc2 Qc6 17. Ra1 $6 d5 $1 {Finally! White's weaknesses make
this advance very effective.} 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bf2 Nxb4 20. Qd2 Nd3 21. Be3
Bc4 $17 {0-1 Leito,P (2355)-Gavrikov,V (2565)/Parnu/Tallinn 2001 (55)} 0-1

