{After getting familiar with the previous example, it will be easier for you
to get point behind the so-called "Magnus concept". I was quite impressed by
the game Carlsen - Anand from Grenke Chess Classic, 2019. After the usual moves
} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {Magnus played the rare} 4. e4 $5 {[%cal Gg1e2,
Gf1g2,Ge1g1] With this move, White practically forces the exchange on c3.
Otherwise, he will proceed with Nge2, thus achieving a harmonious setup. The
position of interest arises after} Bxc3 5. dxc3 {In my comments to the
previous game, I wrote that White should refrain from e2-e4 until Black's ...
Nc6. Otherwise, Black can start preparing the advance ...b7-b5. Magnus,
however, plays e2-e4 with a bishop on f1! This subtle detail changes
everything. The f1-bishop makes it difficult for Black to carry out ...b7-b5.
As we are going to witness, White will further increase his control of the
b5-square by playing Bd3 followed by Qe2.} d6 ({It's important to mention that
} 5... Nxe4 {runs into} 6. Qg4 {when White will regain the pawn under
favourable circumstances.}) 6. f3 {[%cal Gg1h3,Gh3f2] White is planning to
bring his knight to f2 via h3. The critical position arose after} a5 7. Nh3 a4
8. Nf2 Be6 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5,Gg3g4,Gg4g5] When looking at
this position, one can understand the beauty of the entire concept of Magnus.
By employing an optimal piece placement, White managed to prevent Black direct
attempts to create counterplay. Currently, the typical pawn breaks (...b7-b5, .
..d6-d5, and ...f7-f5) do not work. On the other hand, White is ready to start
gaining space on the kingside by means of f3-f4-f5 followed by g3-g4-g5.} c6 $2
{After this serious mistake, Black will be doomed to passivity during the
entire game. After White's next move, it transpires that achieving the advance
...d6-d5 is an illusion.} ({I believe that Black should have tried to achieve .
..b7-b5. I have examined the following sample line:} 10... Nc5 11. Bc2 {
Lc0 v0.26.3:} Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] planning ...b7-b6 followed by ...Qa6.}
12. O-O b6 13. Nd1 Qa6 14. Ne3 O-O 15. Bd2 c6 {[%cal Gb6b5] Finally, Black
seizes the opportunity to prepare ...b6-b5. Nevertheless, after} 16. Rf2 b5 17.
cxb5 cxb5 18. g4 {[%cal Gf2g2,Ge2e1,Ge1h4] I am inclined to believe that
White's kingside initiative shouldn't be underestimated. He can proceed with
simple moves such as Rg2 followed by Qe1-h4. Even though the computer gives
equality, Black needs to be precise in this position.}) 11. f4 $1 {This is the
point. Now, Black cannot get ...d6-d5 due to the threat of f4-f5. After} Nb6
12. Be3 c5 13. O-O-O Qe7 14. f5 Bd7 15. g4 $16 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4] White has a
strategically winning position. He can keep gaining space on the kingside
while Black does not have any counterplay. Even though Anand finally managed
to survive, he was suffering during the entire game.} h6 16. h4 O-O-O 17. g5
Ne8 18. Bd2 hxg5 19. hxg5 Nc7 20. Ng4 Rdg8 21. Rh2 Qf8 22. Rdh1 Kb8 23. b4 axb3
24. axb3 Nc8 25. Kb2 Qd8 26. Rh7 Rxh7 27. Rxh7 Rh8 28. Qh2 Rxh7 29. Qxh7 Qf8
30. Ne3 Ne7 31. Kc2 Qg8 32. Qh4 Qf8 33. Kd1 Nc6 34. Qh7 Ne7 35. Ke2 Nc8 36. Kf2
Ne7 37. Be2 Qg8 38. Qh1 g6 39. Qh6 Ne8 40. f6 Nc6 41. b4 Nc7 42. bxc5 dxc5 43.
Nd5 Ne6 44. Be3 Ka7 45. Bg4 b6 46. Nc7 Qc8 47. Nb5+ Kb8 48. Nd6 Qg8 49. Qh1 Qf8
50. Qd1 Ncd8 51. Nb5 Bc6 52. Kg1 Nc7 53. Bf2 Nb7 54. Bg3 Bxb5 55. cxb5 Qd6 56.
Qe2 Ne6 57. Bxe6 Qxe6 58. Qh2 Qg4 59. Kf2 Qxe4 60. Bxe5+ Kc8 61. Qh3+ Kd8 62.
Qh8+ Kd7 63. Qh3+ Kd8 1/2-1/2

