{[%evp 0,48,13,-7,-14,-14,-14,-26,-20,-49,-3,-19,-7,-7,-6,-12,0,0,6,53,12,25,
25,-14,36,25,82,62,95,98,93,95,86,97,90,119,107,103,169,171,290,297,308,312,
312,312,325,322,339,352,675] Now, we shall take a look at one more example in
which the idea ...c7-c6 followed by ...d6-d5 turned out to be premature.} 1. c4
e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4 Bxc3 5. dxc3 d6 6. f3 Be6 7. Nh3 h6 $6 {In the
concrete position, this move is just a waste of time. White is not planning to
put the knight on g5.} 8. Nf2 Nfd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gc7c6,Gd6d5] Played with the
idea to proceed with ...Nb6 followed by ...c7-c6 and ...d6-d5. Gareyev,
however, uses Black's weak central control and plays the energetic} 9. f4 {
[%csl Re6][%cal Gf4f5] immiediately starting the kingside attack.} f6 $6 {
This is a way too passive.} ({Black should have preferred} 9... exf4 10. gxf4
Qe7 11. Qe2 {with a complex position.}) 10. f5 Bf7 11. g4 Nb6 12. b3 c6 $2 {
Only this move is a real mistake. Black's development is not sufficient to
sustain the break ...d6-d5. As it will become clear soon, this central advance
will only increase the potential of White's bishop pair.} ({More to the point
would have been} 12... a5 13. a4 N8d7 {with a passive but solid position.}) 13.
a4 {[%cal Ga4a5]} d5 $2 14. exd5 cxd5 15. Bg2 $18 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga4a5,Gg2a8]
It turns out that Black cannot hold the centre. His position is falling apart.
White managed to convert the advantage very quickly.} a5 16. Be3 Nc6 17. O-O
Ne7 18. Qd3 Ra6 19. Rad1 O-O 20. cxd5 Qc8 21. c4 Rd8 22. Ne4 Nd7 23. h4 Nf8 24.
Bc5 Ra8 1-0

