{[%evp 0,135,27,-10,-10,-14,-14,-23,-14,-58,-2,-20,-20,-19,-6,-5,7,-14,-4,2,12,
0,-4,3,2,9,14,-17,1,7,26,5,-4,-11,-12,-13,-12,-17,24,-10,11,10,14,5,12,7,5,-2,
5,-1,4,-1,1,-10,-3,-5,54,38,59,44,47,73,71,66,80,65,107,50,100,74,110,112,91,
42,55,152,276,372,372,288,290,292,292,298,303,319,316,304,323,328,326,326,317,
315,305,305,318,318,318,305,307,299,305,305,305,305,327,324,326,326,324,315,
324,319,321,305,305,305,327,321,357,365,367,334,340,364,386,386,402,403,402,
402,411,445,486,445,464,441] The next game has been played almost immediately
after the Grenke Chess Classics. Despite the fact that this was a blitz game,
the opening stage was quite instructive as Karjakin tried an interesting setup.
} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 Bb4 4. e4 Bxc3 5. dxc3 d6 6. f3 O-O 7. Nh3 a6 $5 {
Even though White has a bishop on f1, Karjakin insists on preparing ...b7-b5.
His idea is to provoke the slightly weakening a2-a4 which was played in the
game.} 8. a4 ({If White proceeds with his normal setup, we can see the point
behind 7...a6!?} 8. Nf2 Qe7 9. Bd3 Be6 10. Qe2 Nbd7 11. O-O ({After} 11. f4 $2
exf4 12. gxf4 Nc5 $17 {Black is clearly better since White's position is
overextended.}) 11... Nc5 12. Bc2 b5 $1 {This is the point! Black makes use of
the indirect pressure on the a2-pawn in order to execute his thematic idea.
The game might continue:} 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Qxb5 Rfb8 15. Qe2 Bxa2 16. b4 Nb3
17. Bb1 Bxb1 18. Rxb1 Nxc1 19. Rfxc1 h5 $15 {when Black's position can already
be preferred.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nf2 a5 10. Be2 {Since Black can no longer execute
the advance ...b7-b5 Magnus sees no point in playing Bd3 followed by Qe2.} ({
a normal follow-up would have been} 10. Bd3 Nc5 11. Bc2 Be6 12. Qe2 Nfd7 $1 {
[%cal Gd7b6] Remember this thematic manoeuvre. Besides his idea to provoke
b2-b3 by means of ...Nb6, Black is preparing the typical advance ...f7-f5.} 13.
O-O Nb6 14. b3 f5 {We can now see the point behind provoking b2-b3. In a case
of} 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Rxf5 {[%csl Rb3] White cannot comfortably defend
the b3-pawn. Black has more than sufficient counterplay.}) 10... Nc5 11. O-O
Bd7 12. Be3 b6 13. Kh1 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gf7f5] This is the most precise way
to prepare ...f7-f5. Black is planning to proceed with ...Ng8 followed by ...
f7-f5. The point of putting the knight on g8 (instead of e8) will become clear
very soon.} 14. b3 Ng8 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 15. g4 Ne7 {[%csl Gf4,Gh4][%cal Ge7g6,
Gg6f4,Gg6h4] We can now see why Karjakin was insisting on putting the knight
on g6. The manoeuvre...Ne7-g6 would allow him to take advantage of the
weakened dark-squares.} 16. Rb1 Ng6 17. Qd2 Ne6 18. Nd3 Nc5 $6 {I find this
move dubious. Even though the computer evaluates the position as slightly
better for Black, we shouldn't trust him. As we are going to witness, White
has the idea of gradually gaining space on the kingside.} ({Black should have
played} 18... Nh4 {[%cal Gg7g5] , preparing the advance ...g7-g5. In this case,
only he can be better. While White does not have any clear plan, Black can
prepare ...h7-h5.}) 19. Rg1 Nxd3 20. Bxd3 Bc6 21. Rg3 {[%cal Gb1g1,Gh1g2,Gg2f2,
Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White has an obvious plan at his disposal: 1) Double the
rooks on the g-file 2) Evacuate the king via f2 3) Start advancing the
kingside pawns It turns out that it's not so easy for Black to prevent the
execution of these ideas.} Qe7 22. Rbg1 Kg8 23. Bc2 Kh8 24. Kg2 Kg8 {Failing
to find any constructive idea, Karjakin starts moving the king.} 25. Kf2 f6 26.
Ke1 Kf7 27. g5 {White is already clearly better. Later on, Carlsen managed to
convert the advantage.} Ke8 28. Kd1 Bd7 29. gxf6 Qxf6 30. Bg5 Qe6 31. h4 Rf7
32. h5 Nf8 33. Kc1 g6 34. f4 exf4 35. Bxf4 Bc6 36. e5 dxe5 37. Bxe5 Re7 38.
hxg6 hxg6 39. Bxg6+ Nxg6 40. Rxg6 Qxe5 41. Rg8+ Kf7 42. Qf2+ Ke6 43. R1g6+ Kd7
44. Qd2+ Bd5 45. Rxa8 Qe1+ 46. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 47. Kd2 Bxa8 48. Kxe1 Be4 49. Rg7+
Kd6 50. Kd2 c5 51. Kc1 Kc6 52. Kb2 Bd3 53. Rg4 Be2 54. Rf4 Bd3 55. Rh4 Be2 56.
Kc2 Bf3 57. Rf4 Bh5 58. Rf6+ Kc7 59. b4 Bg4 60. bxc5 bxc5 61. Kd3 Bd1 62. Ke4
Bxa4 63. Kd5 Bb3 64. Kxc5 a4 65. Kb4 Kb7 66. c5 Kc7 67. Ra6 Kb7 68. Rxa4 1-0

