{[%evp 0,32,16,-20,-27,-27,-27,-27,-32,-27,-1,2,45,1,2,11,47,25,10,-24,37,31,
32,25,67,-317,-400,-567,-483,-2032,-29994,-29995,-29996,-29999,-30000] We will
start with a very short game in which I want to illustrate you the strenght of
the h5 plan.} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5 4. Bg2 a6 $5 {This move deserves
serious attention. Black is delaying both "d7-d6" and "Ng8-f6". The point is
simple: Black wants to keep the option to push d5 in one move and to put the
knight on "e7"} 5. e3 (5. a3) 5... Ba7 (5... d6 6. Nge2) 6. Nge2 d6 7. O-O {
Тhis move is a serious innacuracie. Black can now start an attack with h7-h5.
With the king on "e1" the "h5" advance is not that dangerous.} (7. d4 {
deserves attention}) (7. a3 {was Aronian's choice}) 7... h5 8. h4 ({After} 8.
d4 {Black should not react in the centre, but contiue with his plan} h4 $15 {
0-1 (25) Guseinov,G (2666)-Nihal,S (2612) Moscow 2019}) ({The typical reaction
after} 8. h3 {is} h4 9. g4 f5 $1 {With a dangerous initiative.} 10. gxf5 Bxf5
11. d4 Nf6 12. d5 Ne7 $17 {0-1 (32) Mochalin,F (2100)-Korneev,O (2547) Kazan
2018}) 8... Bg4 ({the immediate} 8... g5 $1 {was even stronger}) 9. a3 {
this is too slow} (9. d4) (9. b4 {leads to a complicated position} g5 10. b5
axb5 11. cxb5 Na5 12. d4 gxh4 {Black has good attacking chances, but still
needs to coordinate his pieces. I would probably prefer Black here, but
objectively all three results are possible}) 9... g5 $1 10. hxg5 Qxg5 $19 {
Black's attack can't be stopped anymore and White colapsed in a few moves.} 11.
d4 h4 12. e4 Qh5 13. Re1 hxg3 14. f3 Qh2+ 15. Kf1 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qf2# 0-1

