{We are going to see a model game for White in the "e3-Ne2" variation} 1. c4 e5
2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Bc5 4. Bg2 O-O 5. e3 $1 Re8 6. Nge2 Nc6 7. O-O d6 8. d4 Bb6 9.
h3 $1 {This is our starting position. The game is too old to discuss the move
orders in the opening. Kortschnoj's play from now on is exemplary. With his
last move he prevents any Bg4, Ng4 idea and prepares "g3-g4"} Bf5 (9... exd4 {
the structures after exd4 are always considered slightly better for White,
because of the space advantage and more flexible structure in the centre.} 10.
exd4 h6 {White can choose between b3-Bb2 or Bf4 setups. They both promise
slightly better chances.}) 10. d5 $1 {White wants to advance g3-g4, but before
that, he closes the centre. White's plan is straightforward: g4, Ng3, Kh2
followed by the advance f2-f4} Nb8 (10... Ne7) 11. g4 Bd7 (11... Bg6 {is the
engines choice, but Black was worried that his bishop would be out of play
there.}) 12. Ng3 h6 13. Kh2 a5 14. f4 exf4 (14... Na6 {It was better not to
open the "c1" bishop}) 15. exf4 Nh7 16. g5 $1 {Very nice pawn sacrifice. White
enjoys a free attack when most Black's pieces are stuck on the queenside.} Na6
(16... hxg5 {is losing on the spot} 17. fxg5 Nxg5 18. Qh5 $1 {Black's position
colapsed} f6 19. Bxg5 fxg5 20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. Be4 $1 $18 {the mate is coming
soon.}) (16... f5 $1 {was the best, but it looks very ugly and White should
still win after the simple} 17. h4 $16) 17. gxh6 Qh4 18. hxg7 Nf6 19. f5 $1 {
[%cal Yf1f4,Yc3e4] Strong move. White is activating his pieces and cut the
opponent's bishop from the defense.} Be3 20. Nce4 $1 {White's plan is simple.
He wants to exchange all the defenders of the kingside.} Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxc1 (
21... Rxe4 {is not working due to} 22. Bxe4 Qxe4 23. Qh5 $18) 22. Rxc1 Nc5 23.
Qg4 $1 Rxe4 (23... Qxg4 24. Nf6+ Kxg7 25. Nxe8+ Rxe8 26. hxg4 $18) 24. Bxe4
Qxg4 25. hxg4 Nxe4 26. Rce1 $2 {this move suddenly loses a big part of the
advantage and gives Black a chance to survive.} (26. f6 $1 $18 {was more
accurate. The position is technically winning now.}) 26... Nc5 $2 {Black
didn't use his chance and lost in a few moves} (26... Re8 $2 27. Rf4 $1 Nf6 28.
Rxe8+ Bxe8 29. g5 Nh5 30. Re4 $18 {[%cal Rf5f6]}) (26... Nf6 $3 {Amazing
resource, which I found analyzing the game.} 27. g5 Kxg7 $1 28. gxf6+ Kxf6 29.
Rf2 Rg8 $1 {I am not sure what is the objective evaluation of this position. I
have a feeling that this should be winning with an accurate play. But still, I
think that Black has good chances to survive here in a practical game. Black's
idea is just to play a4 and b6 and to stay. It seems that this is some kind of
fortress. The question is if White will be able to break it. My guess is no,
at least in a practical game.} (29... Bxf5 $13) 30. Rg2 (30. Rg1 Rh8+ 31. Kg2
Rh4 $11) 30... Rh8+ 31. Kg3 Bxf5 $14) 27. f6 Re8 (27... Bxg4 28. Kg3 Bd7 29.
Rh1 $18) 28. Rxe8+ Bxe8 29. Re1 Ba4 30. Re3 {[%cal Re3h3,Rh3h8] Fantastic game}
1-0

