{[%evp 0,99,5,-16,-5,-48,-34,-53,-39,-32,24,7,29,12,29,11,6,3,3,9,11,-6,-5,-49,
-25,-24,-10,-17,-1,7,35,33,25,35,50,21,44,31,42,41,65,5,-2,9,74,29,39,21,56,40,
39,18,81,64,73,58,58,62,49,71,71,70,67,74,78,77,71,65,75,74,88,69,69,75,88,80,
97,79,97,86,86,102,97,87,118,93,90,98,100,100,100,109,115,102,144,141,229,276,
335,380,510,527] In the following game I will try to explain you the structure
where Black plays c6 and d5. I decided to leave this heavily theoretical lines
with 4...c6 out of this lecture. Because they leads to a bit different
strucutures and also they are very well analyzed in the database of Michael
Roiz} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bc5 4. Nc3 c6 {Trendy line. Black is playing
without Nc6 and try to cover the "d5" square with a pawn and also prepares
"d7-d5"} 5. e3 O-O {Of course, there is nothing wrong with this natural move,
which quite ofter transposes to the game.} (5... Bb6 {some players prefers to
play this move first. Black is still flexible and can choose between d7-d5 and
d7-d6}) 6. Nge2 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {This is better than 7...exd5 because the "f6"
knight will be exchanged} (7... Bb6 8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4 cxd5 10. O-O Bg4 11. Qa4
Na6 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qa3 Re8 14. Bd2 Nc5 15. Na4 Nfe4 16. Bc3 Nxa4 17. Qxa4 Rc8
18. Qb3 Qd7 19. Rac1 Rcd8 20. Rc2 Bg6 21. Rcc1 Bh5 (21... Nxg3 22. fxg3 Rxe3)
22. Rc2 Nc5 23. Qa3 Bg6 24. Rcc1 Nd3 25. Rcd1 Be4 26. Ne2 Nxf2 27. Rxf2 Bxe3
28. Nf4 d4 29. Qc5 dxc3) (7... cxd5 $6 {I think that this move is inacurate} 8.
d4 exd4 9. exd4 $14 {Remember this structure guys. It is always worse for
Black. The knight on "e2" is better placed than his colleague on "f6" because
he can attack the "d5" pawn easily. On the other hand, Black's knight can't
attack the "d4" pawn. The best that Black can hope for is to exchange "d5" for
"d4", but even in those symmetrical positions, the problems are not entirely
solved as the following game shows.} Bb6 (9... Bb4 10. O-O $14) 10. Bg5 Nc6 11.
O-O Be6 12. Nf4 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Ncxd5 Bxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd4 16. Qb3 $14 {
[%cal Ra1c1,Ra1d1,Rd5b6] The game finally ended in a draw, but White is better
here. 1/2-1/2 (78) Reinderman,D (2575) -Van Foreest,J (2632) Amstelveen 2019})
8. Nxd5 cxd5 9. d4 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc6 11. Nxc6 (11. O-O $6 Bxd4 12. exd4 Bf5 13.
Be3 Qd7 $11 {Of course, the position is about equal, but strategically is
quite risky for White. If Black manages to exchange the light-squared bishops,
the knight will be better than the dark-squared bishop. The dark-squared
bishop is a defender of the "d4" pawn and the knight is an attacker. Very
quickly, we can transpose to an endgame knight against bishop where Black will
have an advantage. I recommend to all of you to study the famous endgame Saidy
- Fischer.}) 11... bxc6 {The name of this structure is "semi-hanging" pawns.
Black probably has enough counterplay to hold the balance, but, as the
following game shows, the position contains some risks for Black.} 12. O-O {
I will leave the rest of the game without comments because it is not part of
our topic, but you can see how Tomashevsky manages to outplay his opponent and
score a full point.} Bf5 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Rc1 Be7 15. Bc3 Rfd8 16. Qa4 a5 17.
Rfd1 $14 Be6 18. Rd2 Bf8 19. h4 h6 20. Rcd1 Bb4 21. Qc2 Qc5 22. Rc1 Rdc8 23. e4
Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Qxc3 25. Rxc3 Rab8 26. b3 Kf8 27. Rc5 a4 28. bxa4 dxe4 29. Bxe4
Rb4 30. Bxc6 Rxa4 31. Bxa4 Rxc5 32. Bb3 Bxb3 33. axb3 Rc1+ 34. Kg2 Rb1 35. Rd3
Ke7 36. Kf3 Kf6 37. Kf4 g5+ 38. hxg5+ hxg5+ 39. Ke4 Rb2 40. f3 Ke6 41. g4 f6
42. Re3 Rb1 43. Kd4+ Kd6 44. Kc4 Rc1+ 45. Rc3 Rb1 46. b4 Ke5 47. Kc5 f5 48.
gxf5 Kxf5 49. b5 Ke6 50. Kc6 {1-0 (50) Tomashevsky,E (2706)-Svidler,P (2723)
Lichess.org INT 2020} 1-0

