1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 Bc5 5. Nf3 {After we examined the systems
with Nge2, it is time to check the positions where White plays Nf3. This setup
is advocated by Mihail Marin and was tried by Carlsen, Karpov and many other
top players.} d6 6. d3 h6 {It is always useful to stop Bg5} 7. O-O O-O 8. a3 a6
(8... a5 $5 {is another possible setup that we will discuss in the other games}
) (8... Nd4) 9. b4 Ba7 10. Bb2 Be6 {The alternatives are discussed in the next
games. Let's talk a bit about this position. White has two plans in this
structure: 1.To play Nd5.2. To prepare d3-d4 With his last move (Be6) Black is
trying to stop Nd5 and d3-d4 (the c4 pawn is hanging). Black is also preparing
Qd7-Bh3. The other idea is d6-d5 which is not so easy to be played here
because of the "e5" pawn's vulnerability. So what to do? White can try to
prepare Nd5 with Nd2, but then "d6-d5" becomes an option. So White's best
strategy is to improve his position slowly by means of Rc1, e3, followed by d4
in an appropriate moment.} 11. Rc1 Qd7 (11... d5 $2 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5
14. e4 Be6 15. Nxe5 $16) 12. e3 Bh3 13. d4 exd4 (13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 exd4 15.
exd4 $1 $14 {It seems to me that White is slightly better here because of his
space advantage. He can improve the position by means of Qd3, Re1, Ne2. It is
not so clear what is Black's counterplay.} (15. Nd5 $6 {Is our typical strike,
but it is not working here.} Nxd5 $1 16. cxd5 Ne7 $11)) 14. Nd5 (14. exd4 Bg4
$1 {[%csl Gd4]}) 14... Nxd5 (14... dxe3 $4 15. Bxf6 $1 $18) (14... Bxg2 $2 15.
Nxf6+ $1 gxf6 16. Kxg2 dxe3 17. Nh4 $1 $14) 15. cxd5 $6 (15. Bxh3 $1 {This
move gives White better chances than in the game, but I am not convinced that
it is enough for advantage.} Qxh3 16. cxd5 Ne5 $1 (16... Ne7 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18.
Qxd4 $14 {White is better due to the weakness of the "c7" pawn.}) 17. Nxe5 dxe5
18. exd4 e4 $3 (18... exd4 19. Rxc7 $16) 19. Rxc7 f5 $1 20. f4 {I feel that
Black has not enough compensation for the pawn, but still the game remains
complex} Rf7 $1 21. Rxf7 Kxf7 $13) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Ne7 $1 (16... Ne5 17.
Nxd4 $14) 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Qxd4 {Usually, this is What White wants to achieve:
space advantage + play against the backward pawn on "c7". The problem in this
position is that White's pawn is on "b4" which gives Black an immediate
counterplay and level the chances.} a5 $1 $11 19. Rfd1 (19. b5 Qxb5 $11) (19.
Rc4 axb4 20. axb4 c6 21. dxc6 bxc6 $11) 19... axb4 20. axb4 Ra4 $11 {The game
ended in a draw, but not without some adventures. I will leave the rest
without comments.} 21. Qc3 Rc8 22. Rd4 c5 23. dxc6 Rxc6 24. Rc4 Rxc4 25. Qxc4
Nc6 26. Rd1 Rxb4 27. Qd3 Rb2 28. Qxd6 Qf5 29. Qa3 Qb5 30. Qa8+ Kh7 31. Qc8 Ne7
32. Qd7 Qc5 33. Qd4 Qxd4 34. Rxd4 b5 35. Rd7 Nf5 36. Kf1 h5 37. Nd4 $138 Nxd4
1/2-1/2

