{[%evp 0,168,19,-20,-20,-37,-34,-34,-20,-13,-7,-8,-11,-12,3,-1,-1,-4,16,15,10,
10,9,9,24,24,34,35,30,21,16,9,19,23,19,0,9,-3,4,9,1,3,2,-1,21,3,19,13,23,-8,-4,
-16,-16,-21,-10,-10,-24,-12,-2,-3,-23,-14,8,-7,-7,10,19,0,0,11,8,-50,-50,-50,
-57,-57,-57,-55,-58,-58,-53,-53,-53,-53,-61,-127,-67,-69,-69,-69,-69,-86,-86,
-91,-82,-98,-105,-114,-98,-97,-86,-86,-91,-85,-85,-85,-85,-113,-112,-99,-102,
-101,-104,-116,-93,-115,-114,-140,-126,-126,-104,-106,-46,-89,-125,-157,-156,
-194,-156,-178,-216,-234,-208,-224,-264,-275,-238,-290,-296,-289,-300,-333,
-335,-310,-349,-432,-434,-434,-413,-414,-457,-475,-494,-521,-130,-139,-7,-177,
-195,-198,-239,-282,-315,-507,-517,-507,-537,-537,-547,-547,-547]} 1. c4 e5 2.
g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. Nc3 Bc5 5. Nf3 d6 6. d3 a6 7. O-O O-O 8. a3 (8. Bg5 $5 {
The immediate Bg5 is not giving any benefits for White after:} h6 $1 9. Bxf6 ({
White can try to set a trap} 9. Bh4 Nd4 $1 {is the only move here, but it is
enough to maintain the ballance} (9... g5 $4 10. Nxg5) 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Ne4
Qe7 12. Nxc5 dxc5 13. Nxd4 exd4 {and I would take Black}) 9... Qxf6 10. Ne4 Qe7
11. Nxc5 dxc5 $15 {with a small but stable advantage for Black due to the
threat f5-e4}) 8... Nd4 9. b4 {allowing the knights' exchange also doesn't
pose any problems for Black} (9. Nd2 {This move doesn't lead to advantage} c6
10. b4 Ba7 11. Bb2 Bf5 {Karpov likes this move a lot} (11... Bg4 {is also
possible}) 12. e3 Ne6 {I called this "Karpov's maneuvre" In many omaneuvermes,
he transfers the knight to "e6"} 13. Nf3 h6 {The plan is to continue with Bh7,
Ne8, f5-f4 0-1 (36) Gelfand,B (2700)-Karpov, A (2765) Sanghi Nagar 1995 CBM
045 [Ftacnik,L]}) (9. Ne1 $5 {This is the favorite approach of GM Boris Gulko,
who scores 1.5 out of 2 with it. It is quite rare but deserves attention.
White's plan is to kick the knight from "d4", then to return on "f3" and start
gaining space on the queenside by means of b4-c5.} c6 10. e3 Nf5 (10... Ne6 11.
b4 Ba7 12. Nf3 {[%cal Rc1b2,Ra1c1,Rc3e4] With a bishop still on "c8" this
setup is not that good for Black. The position should be around equal, but for
me, it seems that White's play is easier.}) 11. Nf3 Ba7 12. b4 Re8 13. Bb2 Rb8
(13... d5 14. e4 $6 (14. c5 $6 $16) 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nd4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (22)
Gulko,B (2606)-Cramling,P (2496) Malmo 2001}) 14. Rc1 b5 15. c5 dxc5 16. Ne4 {
with an intiative for White 1-0 (31) Gulko,B (2580)-Sadler,M (2665) Luzern
1997 CBM 062}) 9... Nxf3+ $1 10. Bxf3 Bd4 11. Bb2 c6 12. e3 Ba7 13. Rc1 Bh3 (
13... d5 {also deserves attention, but I prefer Grandelius' plan}) 14. Re1 Qd7
15. Ne4 {This move only helps Black} Nxe4 16. dxe4 Rad8 17. Rc2 Qe6 $1 {
the start of a very deep idea} 18. Qd3 Bb8 19. Rd2 Bc7 {Before starting any
concrete actions (f5) Black first improves his position to maximum. White's
main problem is that there is no active plan} 20. Rc1 h6 21. Bc3 Qe7 {freeing
the e6 square for the bishop} 22. Rb1 Be6 23. a4 f6 24. Rc2 Qf7 25. Be1 f5 {
everything is ready for this break now} 26. exf5 Bxf5 27. Be4 Bxe4 (27... Bh3 {
makes more sense to me}) 28. Qxe4 d5 29. cxd5 cxd5 30. Qd3 e4 31. Qe2 Be5 {
Once this bishop was Black's most passive piece, he will now decide the game.
The advance d5-d4 will come soon.} 32. b5 axb5 33. Rxb5 d4 34. exd4 Bxd4 35.
Qc4 (35. Bc3 $1 $11) 35... Bxf2+ 36. Bxf2 Rd1+ 37. Kg2 Qxc4 38. Rxc4 Rd2 39.
Rxe4 Rfxf2+ 40. Kh3 Rxh2+ 41. Kg4 {This should be holdable, but Grandelius
manages to convert it to a full point} Rd3 42. Rbe5 Kh7 43. Re3 Rd6 44. Re6
Rdd2 45. R6e5 Ra2 46. R5e4 Rhb2 47. Rf3 Rb6 48. Kh3 Rb1 49. Kg4 Rba1 50. Rff4
Ra3 51. Re7 Rg1 52. Rxb7 Rgxg3+ 53. Kf5 Rg5+ 54. Ke6 h5 55. Ra7 Kg6 56. Ra6 Rg1
57. Ke7+ Kg5 58. Rf7 Kh4 59. Rf5 g6 60. Re5 Rf3 61. Rb6 Rf5 62. Rb4+ Kg5 63.
Re6 h4 64. Rbb6 Kh5 65. Re3 Rg3 66. Re2 h3 67. Rb8 g5 68. Ke6 Kg4 69. Rh8 Rff3
70. Rb2 Rg2 71. Rb5 h2 72. a5 Re2+ 73. Kd6 Rf1 74. Rb4+ Kg3 75. Rb3+ Kg2 76.
Rhh3 g4 77. Rbg3+ Kf2 78. Rxh2+ Kxg3 79. Rxe2 Ra1 80. Re5 Kf4 81. Ke6 g3 82.
Rf5+ Kg4 83. Kf6 g2 84. Rg5+ Kf3 0-1

