1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 Bc5 4. Bg2 d6 5. a3 a6 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nf3 h6 8. O-O O-O
9. b4 Ba7 10. e3 Be6 11. Bb2 Qd7 12. Rc1 {We discussed the opening moves in
the game - Marin - Navara In this game, Fedorchuk chooses 12...Ne7 instead of
12...Bh3} Ne7 {The idea is to transfer the knight to g6, put a pawn on c6, and
then start an attack on the kingside by means of Bh3 followed by f5} 13. d4 $1
{The best move. White needs to play dynamically since the Black knight is
still on e7} exd4 (13... Bxc4 $2 14. dxe5 $16) 14. Nxd4 (14. exd4) 14... Bxc4 {
The only principled move. After everything else, White is better} ({for example
} 14... Bh3 15. Nf3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $14 {[%cal Rd1d3,Rc3e2,Re2f4]}) 15. Ne4 Nxe4
$6 ({I decided to investigate this position in great depth because it seems
critical for evaluating White's idea.} 15... Bxf1 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxf1 Ng6 {
Until now, everything is forced, but now White can choose between different
plans. The most promising one is:} 18. Nf3 {The idea is to open the long
diagonal and to transfer the knight to "h4," trying to exchange the only
defender of Black's king} c6 {the attempts to defend the pawn are not working
well for Black} (18... Qe7 $2 19. Nh4 $1 Nxh4 20. gxh4 $18 {White is winning.
The plan is Qh5,Bd3,Kh1, Rg1}) (18... Kg7 $5 19. Rc4 $1 {Only this move
promises an advantage} b5 20. Rh4 $1 {computer chess} Rae8 21. Bh3 {[%cal
Rh4h5,Rh5f5]} Qd8 22. Rh5 $14 {[%cal Rf3h4,Rh3f5,Rd1g4]}) 19. Bxf6 Rfe8 20. Bb2
$13 {I analyzed this much further, but the game is not forced, and we can
already make some conclusions. I believe that White is better. He has the
initiative and a clear plan to attack the king. On the other hand, Black has a
material advantage and can defend this according to the engines. The
evaluation of some powerful engines is 0.00, but I would always prefer White
and think that the position is practically almost winning}) 16. Rxc4 d5 17.
Bxe4 dxc4 $2 {this move loses by force} (17... dxe4 {is the safest option.
Navara had this position ten years ago with Black pieces and survived} 18. Nc6
Qe6 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Qc2 (20. Qd5 $5 $14) 20... c6 21. Rxe4 $14 {1/2 (34)-1/
2 (34) Matamoros Franco,C (2542)-Navara,D (2722) Khanty-Mansiysk 2010}) (17...
Rfd8 18. Bh7+ Kh8 (18... Kxh7 $2 19. Qc2+ Kg8 20. Rxc7 $18) 19. Bf5 Nxf5 20.
Nxf5 Qxf5 21. Rxc7 $14 {1-0 (44) Artemiev,V (2746)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2629)
Douglas 2019}) 18. Nf5 $1 Qe6 (18... Qxd1 {was the only way to continue the
game} 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Rxd1 $16) 19. Qg4 Ng6 20. Bd5 h5 21. Qxh5 (21. Ne7+ {
[%emt 0:00:06] is mate in 6}) 21... Qxd5 22. Nh6+ gxh6 23. Qxd5 $18 {the rest
is agony} b5 24. Qc6 f6 25. Rd1 Bb6 26. Rd7 Rae8 27. Qd5+ Kh8 28. Qh5 Ne7 29.
Bxf6+ Kg8 30. Bxe7 Rf7 31. Qg6+ 1-0

