{[%evp 0,15,19,-12,-27,-33,-24,-51,12,12,6,13,-2,3,28,30,33,5]} 1. c4 e5 2. Nc3
Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 {This is the starting position of the system called
"Reversed closed Sicilian". White has several plans of development, but only
one is typical for our main theme, the mutual attacks on opposite wings.} 5. d3
(5. e3 {[%cal Gg1e2] followed by Nge2 and d2-d4, is a solid plan, but it
causes the game to lose the English contours after the pawn reaches d4.}) 5...
d6 6. Nf3 {This move maintains the structural flexibility, ensuring White long
term chances for a better ending or a strategic advantage in the middlegame.
The fact that he gives up any attempts at fighting for space in the centre,
makes this setup suitable for examining the ideas connected with our main
theme. White is simply bound to attack on the queenside.} ({I have played
Botvinnik's} 6. e4 {many times, but it is obvious that after this move the
focus is on the centre.}) ({I have also tried} 6. e3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg1e2]})
({and} 6. Rb1 a5 7. e3 {, but once again, the importance of the centre is big
in these systems. This makes it more difficult to examine the attacks on the
opposite wings. In fact, Black's kingside chances are not that high, since
White can react with f2-f4 to any aggressive attempt.}) 6... f5 {The most
aggressive move, preparing a massive kingside attack.} ({We will also briefly
deal with} 6... Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Rb1 {, even though in this case Black's
attack is not so obvious. True, White's plan remains the same.}) 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Rb1 {This is the starting point of most of the examples examined below.
White's plan in the first phase is simple. He will advance his b-pawn to b5,
gaini9ng space and forcing the knight to weaken the defence on e5. This way,
Black cannot issue ambitions based on ...d6-d5 easily, on the condition that
White keeps his knight on f3 for a long time.} a5 ({The main alternative is} 
8... O-O 9. b4 h6 10. b5 Ne7) 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 h6 12. b5 Ne7 {
Things become more complicated after the first phase. White's position looks
pleasing aesthetically, due to his control on light squares, but without
opening files and diagonals he cannot make progress. Black's positional attack
is more consistent since he can use a wider space. On the other hand,
advancing all his kingside pawns and regrouping with the pieces behind them is
time-consuming. We will start by illustrating a few typical situations.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Example 1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "5rk1/1ppnnqb1/3pb2p/1P2ppp1/1QP5/2NP2P1/1B1NPPBP/R5K1 b - - 0 19"]
[PlyCount "2"]

{[#]Both sides have massed their pieces on "their" wings. White's queenside
pressure is more obvious (he can increase it with Ra7) but, as said, Black's
attack can acquire a global character.} 19... f4 $2 {In all sorts of Sicilian
systems, f4-f5 is a typical way of starting the attack. The drawback of ...
f5-f4 in our structure is that it weakens the square on e4, yielding White
clear domination on light squares.} (19... e4 $1 {was the best way of starting
the attack.} 20. dxe4 (20. Ra7 Nc5) 20... f4 {An operation resembling White's
central break in the Penrose Benoni. The e4-pawn stands in the way of many
white minor pieces and Black has the perfect blocking e5-square.}) 20. Rf1 $16
{Ljubojevic,L (2548)-Piket,J (2659) Monte Carlo 2002 (1-0, 42) More about this
game later.} (20. Nce4 $16) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Example 2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/ppp3b1/3p1nnp/1P2ppp1/P1P5/B1NP1NP1/4PPBP/1R1Q1RK1 w - - 0 13"]
[PlyCount "23"]

{[#]Black has neglected his development in order to reach the attacking setup
as soon as possible. The former aspect exposes him to a typical break.} 13. c5
$1 {Opening the c-file and creating a weakness on d6.} Be6 (13... Rf7 14. cxd6
cxd6 15. Qb3 d5 16. Nd2 {Black's delay in development is obvious now.} e4 (
16... d4 17. Nd5 Be6 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Bd5 $16 {with fantastic play for White.
He can continue with Rfc1 and Nc4, preparing a complete invasion.}) (16... Be6
17. e4 $16) 17. dxe4 dxe4 18. Ncxe4 fxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 $16 {[%csl Rg6]
[%cal Ge4d5,Gf1d1] After Rfd1 and Bd5 White will not be worse from a material
point of view. His advance in development and the vulnerable enemy king offers
him a clear advantage.}) (13... dxc5 14. Bxc5 Re8 15. Nd2 {One of the clearest
situations when Black's delay in development counts. Due to the bishops'
pressure on b7 and a7, he does not have obvious ways of completing his
development.}) 14. Nd2 Rb8 (14... d5 15. c6 Rf7 16. cxb7 Rb8 17. Nb3 $18) 15.
a5 {It is White's attack which became global now.} Rf7 (15... d5 16. c6 Rf7 17.
cxb7 Rxb7 18. Nb3 Rb8 19. Nc5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1b3] AFter Qb3, Black will
not be able to maintain the control over d5.}) (15... Re8 16. b6 axb6 17. cxd6
cxd6 18. Rxb6 d5 19. Nb5 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. b6 a6 18. e4 $1 {
AFter having obtained a full success on the queenside, White starts fighting
for space in the centre.} f4 19. Nd5 g4 20. Nc7 Qd7 21. Re1 $1 {Clearing the
f1-square for the bishop.} Rd8 (21... f3 22. Bf1) 22. Nc4 Bf8 23. Rc1 h5 24. d4
$16 {Zhou,J (2619)-Grigoryan,K (2482) Moscow 2012 (1-0, 60)} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Example 3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "5r1k/2p5/1p1p1b1p/1P1Qp1p1/2P2p2/3P2Pq/1B2PP1P/R5K1 w - - 0 27"]
[PlyCount "45"]

{[#] The pawn break c4-c5 is an important method of clearing space for the
attack. In the previous game, everything went smoothly, but sometimes this
break implies a pawn sacrifice. White has achieved complete control on light
squares. In the endgame, the black bishop is likely to be "bad" Now is a good
moment to mention Bronstein's comment regarding the weakness of (in our case)
light squares. At first thought, Black is safe because he has placed his pawns
and all but one piece on dark squares, not controlled by White. But as
Bronstein understood at a certain moment, White's pieces (the queen and
several pawns) placed on light squares attack the dark squares! It is also
worth mentioning that Black is a few tempi away from creating serious threats 
(for instance, ...g5-g4, ...Bg7 and ...f4-f3).} 27. Ra8 $2 {White wrongly
assumed that he would have winning chances in an ending with a good bishop
versus a bad one. Instead, he should have attacked the enemy pawn chain.} (27.
c5 $1 bxc5 (27... dxc5 28. Ra7 $5 Qc8 29. Qc6 $18 {Of course, taking on e5 in
several moments was also good.}) 28. b6 cxb6 29. Qxd6 Rf7 30. Qxb6 $16 {
White will win the pawn on c5 and maintain attacking chances.}) (27. Ra7 $1 Qf5
(27... Rc8 28. Qf7) (27... Bd8 28. c5 $1 bxc5 29. b6 $1 {Black cannot take on
b6 due to Qb7 with a mate in sight.} fxg3 30. hxg3 Qf5 31. f3 Qh3 32. bxc7
Qxg3+ 33. Kf1) (27... Qc8 28. c5 $16) 28. f3 g4 29. Rxc7 fxg3 30. hxg3 gxf3 31.
Qxf3 $16) (27. d4 $6 {is less effective, since it implies exchanging the
bishops soon.} Qf5 $14) 27... Rxa8 28. Qxa8+ Kg7 29. Qc6 Qc8 30. Kg2 Qd8 31. g4
Qe7 32. h3 {Optically, White has a large advantage, but Black's fortress is
impossible to break.} Qf7 33. Kf1 h5 34. Ba3 hxg4 35. hxg4 Bd8 36. Bb2 Qe6 37.
f3 Kf7 38. Bc3 Qe8 39. Qe4 Qe6 40. Ke1 Ke8 41. Kd2 Bf6 42. Kc2 Kd7 43. Kb3 Bd8
44. Bd2 ({The only (slight) chance was preparing the break with d3-d4.} 44. Be1
Bf6 45. Bf2 Ke7 46. Kc3 Kd7 47. d4 exd4+ 48. Kd3 Qxe4+ 49. Kxe4 Ke6 50. Bxd4
Bxd4 51. Kxd4 Kf6 52. Ke4 (52. Kd5 Ke7 53. Kc6 Kd8 $11 54. Kb7 $4 Kd7 55. Kb8
d5 56. cxd5 Kd6 57. Kc8 Kxd5 58. Kxc7 Kc5 $19) 52... Ke6 53. e3 fxe3 54. Kxe3
Ke5 55. f4+ gxf4+ 56. Kf3 d5 57. cxd5 Kxd5 58. Kxf4 c5 59. bxc6 Kxc6 60. g5 Kd7
$11) 44... Qh6 45. Bc3 Qe6 46. e3 (46. d4 exd4 47. Qxe6+ Kxe6 48. Bxd4 Bf6 49.
Bf2 d5 $1) 46... fxe3 47. Qxe3 Qg6 48. Kb2 Bf6 49. Qe4 {½-½ Hickl, J (2631)
-Jussupow, A (2598) Switzerland 2013} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
