[Result "*"]
[ECO "A26"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "30"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Nf3 f5 7. O-O Nf6 8. Rb1 {
After having examined a few typical situations, I will propose some sort of
repertoire, which can be used with either White or Black, even though the
focus is a bit on White.} a5 {This is considered to be the main variation. In
order to gain queenside space, White will have to open the a-file for Black's
rook, while his attack will never be "global" after the exchange of one pawn.
On the other hand, White can later use the a-file for himself, even though
this is connected with losing time. Finally, there is this old rule saying:
"Do not move the pawns on the wing where you are going to be under attack!"} ({
In view of all these,} 8... O-O {is not to be underestimated.} 9. b4 h6 10. b5
Ne7 11. a4 Be6 $1 ({We already know that delaying the queenside development is
dangerous:} 11... g5 12. Ba3 Ng6 13. c5 {Zhou, J (2619)-Grigoryan, K (2482)
Moscow 2012 (1-0, 60)}) 12. Ba3 {More about this later, Psakhis, L (2575)
-Kasparov,G (2800) Murcia 1990 (0-1, 30)}) 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 h6
12. b5 Ne7 13. Bb2 {White should just develop and leave the knight on f3 in
order to inhibit a central break.} (13. c5 {is premature.} Be6 14. Bb2 (14. b6
c6 $5) 14... Nfd5 {with active play.}) 13... Be6 (13... g5 $6 14. c5 Be6 15. b6
c6 16. Ra1 $1 {The difference in development is important move by move.}) 14.
Ra1 $1 {White immediately starts the fight for the open file. This situation
with tension along the a-file is interesting. General rules recommend
maintaining the tension.} g5 {I find this best and in perfect accordance with
the rule above, but curiously the move is not too popular.} (14... Rb8 {
is a clear concession} 15. Ra7 Nc8 16. Ra5 {Nihal,S (2471)-Lerch,P (2320)
Pardubice 2017 (1-0, 55)}) (14... Rxa1 {also concedes White the control over
the open file.} 15. Qxa1 g5 16. Qa7 b6 17. Rc1 (17. Ra1 {Paunovic,D (2511)
-Fernando Gros,J (2081) Ortigueira 2004 (1-0, 37)}) 17... Rf7 18. Nd2 {Van
Wely,L (2625) -Movsesian,S (2751) Wijk aan Zee 2009 (0-1, 44)}) 15. Qb3 $5 (15.
Rxa8 {is a mini-concession from White} Qxa8 {Ljubojevic,L (2548)-Piket,J (2659)
Monte Carlo 2002 (1-0, 42)}) 15... Qd7 {Forster,M (1982)-Hynes,A (2102)
England 2017 (0-1, 43) This is the main scheme, now we will examine the games
mentioned at the end of each line.} *

