1. c4 e5 {The English Opening is undoubtedly one of the most frequent guests
in the current tournament practice. Nearly all the elite players, headed by
the World Champion, are often relying on it, contributing to its theory.
Carlsen himself is constantly surprising us with tricky move orders. Here I
will try to describe the latest tendencies after 1.. .e5, which are closely
connected with many of the main Sicilian variations.} 2. Nc3 {The main
continuation, but the players as White has not limited themselves to it:} ({
A lot of preference is given nowadays to} 2. g3 Nf6 (2... c6 {was the subject
of a database of mine for Modern Chess}) 3. Bg2 {and now:} d5 (3... c6 $5 {
is once again a very serious option}) ({In case of} 3... Nc6 4. Nc3 Bc5 $5 {
is critical in my opinion.} ({White has more options at his disposal against} 
4... Bb4 {, for example} 5. Nd5 {[%csl Gg1]} Bc5 6. e3 d6 7. Ne2 $14) 5. e3 (5.
Nf3 {may transpose to one of the widely discussed variations after} O-O 6. O-O
d5) 5... d5 6. cxd5 Nb4 7. d3 Nfxd5 8. Nxd5 Nxd5 9. Nf3 Qe7 10. O-O O-O 11. b3
c6 12. Bb2 Bd6 13. Nd2 Ba3 14. Bxa3 Qxa3 15. Nc4 Qe7 16. Qd2 Rd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(44) Ding,L (2791)-Yu,Y (2709) chess24.com INT 2020}) 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 {
A new fashion - for long White has preferred to hold the development of this
knight in favour of 5.Nc3. Indeed, it remains a reasonable weapon, but the
roles of the minor pieces have recently changed a bit.} Nc6 6. O-O Nb6 (6...
Be7 {is not proper, for} 7. d4 $1 {is difficult to meet:} e4 (7... exd4 8. Nxd4
Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nf6 (9... Nb4 $2 {is nicely refuted by} 10. Qxg7 Bf6 11. Qh6 Nc2
12. Nc3 Nxa1 13. Rd1 Bd7 14. Nd5 $18) 10. Qa4+ c6 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 13.
Bxc5 Qxc5 14. b4 Qb6 15. Na3 O-O 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Qa5 $14 {with pressure in the
Catalan manner.}) 8. Ne5 f5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qc2 $14) ({the active-looking} 
6... Bc5 $2 {has become popular against a similar line, in which the other
knight is already on its usual c3-square instead of castling, but in our case
it is just falling to the typical} 7. Nxe5 $16 {[%cal Gd2d4]}) 7. b3 {is the
new modern set-up, initiating interesting fight for the central squares:} Be6 (
7... Bd6 {This overprotection of the central pawn has been used by MVL.} 8. Nc3
O-O 9. d4 $5 (9. Bb2 {leads to a very complex game, which seems satisfactory
for Black -} Re8 ({or} 9... f5 $5) 10. d3 Bf8 11. Rc1 f6 $13) 9... Bb4 (9...
Nxd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 $14) (9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 $14) 10. Bb2
{sharpens the game:} exd4 (10... Bxc3 $5 $146 11. Bxc3 Nd5 (11... e4 12. Ne5
$14) 12. Be1 e4 13. Ne5 $14) (10... Nxd4 $6 11. Nxe5 Re8 12. Nd5 $1 Nxe2+ 13.
Kh1 Bf8 14. Nxb6 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 axb6 16. Rd2 f6 17. Bd5+ Be6 18. Bxb7 $16) 11.
Nb5 {The distinguished English GM has apparently got attracted by the similar
operation (see the next subline) by Hammer against him.} d3 12. Qxd3 Qxd3 13.
exd3 Nd5 14. Ne5 Nxe5 $146 (14... Nce7 $6 15. a3 Bc5 16. Rac1 Bb6 17. Nc4 c6
18. Nbd6 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Adams,M (2694)-Studer,N (2546) Caleta 2020}) 15.
Bxe5 c6 $11) (7... Be7 8. Bb2 f6 {Put together with the leading line 7...?e6
