1. c4 e5 2. d3 {I think that this system is a very interesting choice for
White. Given the flexibility of the pawn structure, both sides have a lot of
freedom. This is always good when you try to get a playable position without
fearing computer preparations.} g6 {One of the many decent options.} ({I
believe that Black's best setup is} 2... Bb4+ 3. Nd2 c5 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gg8e7,
Gb4a5] Black gains space and plans to proceed with ...Nc6 and ...Nge7. Thanks
to the move ...c7-c5, the dark-squared bishop can be rerouted to c7 via a5.} 4.
g3 ({Another option would be} 4. e3 Nc6 5. Be2 Nf6 6. Ngf3 O-O 7. O-O Ba5 ({
After} 7... d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5 (8... Nxd5 9. Nc4) 9. a3 Ba5 10. Qc2 {White gets a
favourable version of the Hedgehog due to the exposed queen on d5.}) ({A
decent alternative is} 7... Bxd2 8. Bxd2 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. a3 Qd6 {when
Black's space advantage compensates for the bishop pair.}) 8. Ne4 (8. a3 d6 9.
Qc2 h6 10. b3 Qe7 (10... Nh7 11. Bb2 f5 12. b4 cxb4 13. c5) 11. Bb2 Kh8 12. Ne4
Nxe4 13. dxe4 f5 14. g3 g5 15. b4) 8... Nxe4 9. dxe4 d6 10. Bd2 Bxd2 11. Qxd2
Qe7 12. Rad1 Rd8 13. Ne1 Be6 14. Nc2 a6 {Black is doing fine.}) (4. Ngf3 Nc6 {
is just a transposition.}) 4... Nc6 5. Bg2 Nge7 6. Ngf3 O-O 7. O-O Ba5 8. Ne4 {
This is White's most natural way of completing the development.} ({After} 8.
Qc2 d6 9. a3 h6 10. e3 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8c8] Black is getting a
comfortable position.}) 8... d6 9. Bd2 Bxd2 10. Nfxd2 b6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6,
Gd8d7,Gd6d5] Black enjoys a perfectly sound position. His idea would be to
prepare the advance ...d6-d5 by means of ...f7-f6 followed by ...Qd7 and ...
d6-d5.}) 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. g3 Ne7 $5 {This move indicates Black's intention of
playing ...c7-c6 followed by ...d7-d5.} ({After} 4... d6 {I would chose the
Botvinnik setup which arises after} 5. Bg2 Nc6 {[%cal Ge2e3,Ge2e4,Gg1f3]} 6. e4
{White is ready to follow with Nge2, 0-0, Be3, and Rb1 followed by b2-b4-b5.
This setup was very well covered by Michael Roiz in one of his databases for
Modern Chess.}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. e4 ({Another option would have been} 6. h4 {After
} h6 (6... h5 7. Nf3 {[%csl Gg5]}) 7. h5 g5 8. f4 {White keeps an initiative.})
6... c6 ({After} 6... Nbc6 {we can play} 7. Nge2 d6 8. O-O a6 9. Nd5 Bg4 10. f3
Be6 11. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gb2b4] reaching a standard position for the
Botvinnik setup.}) 7. Nge2 Na6 8. O-O Nc7 9. Be3 d5 {Black finally managed to
execute his main idea. I believe my reaction was very precise -} 10. exd5 cxd5
11. Bc5 $1 $36 d4 12. Ne4 b6 13. Ba3 $14 {White managed to achieve a
favourable version of the Benoni Defence with colours reversed. Instead of
having a problematic bishop on c1, White has a monster on a3. At any moment,
Black should reckon with the possible Nd6 idea.} Rb8 14. Nd6 Bd7 15. Nb7 Qe8
16. Nd6 Qd8 17. f4 b5 18. Qe1 Nf5 $5 (18... a5 19. cxb5 (19. Qxa5 Nc6) 19...
Nxb5 20. Nb7 Rxb7 21. Bxb7 Nxa3 22. bxa3 Nf5) 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. Bxf8 Qxf8 21.
fxe5 Bxd3 22. cxb5 Rxb5 (22... Bxb5 $44 {[%csl Gb5]}) 23. Qd2 Bxe2 24. Qxe2
Rxe5 25. Qc4 Ne6 (25... Rc5) 26. Rae1 Rc5 27. Qa6 Qd8 28. Qxa7 Rc7 29. Qa8 $1
Qxa8 30. Bxa8 Bh6 (30... Ra7 31. Bd5 {[%cal Gd5a2]}) 31. Bd5 Bd2 32. Re2 Be3+
33. Kg2 Nc5 34. b4 $18 Na4 35. b5 Kg7 36. Bb3 Nc5 37. b6 Rb7 38. Bd5 Rxb6 39.
Rxf7+ Kh6 40. h4 Rd6 41. Bc4 g5 42. hxg5+ Bxg5 43. Re5 Nd7 44. Bd3 Nf6 45. Re1
1-0

