1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Nd5 a5 $5 {Currently, this is a fashionable way of
meeting 3.Nd5. Recently, Anand started playing this move almost exclusively.
Black gains space on the queenside and secures the c5-square for the bishop.
Additionally, this move makes the a7-square available for the bishop. As we
are going to witness a bit later, this is a very important detail.} 4. a3 ({
The structure arising after} 4. g3 Ne7 5. Bg2 Nxd5 6. cxd5 {is quite typical
for the variation. In order to fight for the centre and eliminate the pressure
on the c-file, Black should play ...c7-c6 as soon as possible. For example,
after} O-O 7. e3 c6 8. a3 Be7 9. d4 d6 10. Ne2 cxd5 11. Nc3 Nd7 12. O-O Nf6 {
Black was doing fine in the game 1/2 (34) Li, C (2725)-Wang, Y (2679) Hangzhou
2018}) 4... Bc5 5. Nf3 {The most logical move.} ({The position arising after} 
5. e3 Nf6 6. d4 Nxd5 7. cxd5 exd4 8. exd4 Bb6 9. Bd3 Qe7+ 10. Ne2 O-O 11. O-O
d6 {is quite comfortable for Black. He has good counterplay due to the
superior structure. 1/2 (86) Ivanchuk,V (2679) -Bosiocic,M (2598) Zagreb 2019})
({When playing this line, you should be aware of the following forced sequence:
} 5. b4 axb4 6. Bb2 Nc6 7. axb4 Rxa1 8. Qxa1 Nxb4 9. Nxb4 Bxb4 10. Bxe5 Nf6 11.
e3 O-O {with a decent position for Black.}) 5... d6 6. e3 {This move allows
Black to realize his setup.} ({In my opinion, White's most critical option is} 
6. d4 $5 exd4 7. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc4,Rd5,Rd6] Structurally speaking, White is
better due to the space provided by the c4-pawn. On the other hand, Black has
dynamic resources based on White's unstable d5-knight.} Ne7 8. Bg5 (8. b3 Nbc6)
8... f6 9. Bf4 O-O 10. e3 Nbc6 11. Nb5 (11. Nb3 Ba7 12. Be2 a4 13. Nd2 Bd7 14.
O-O Nxd5 15. cxd5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6]}) 11... Nxd5 12. cxd5 Ne5 {1/2 (34)
Koestner, W (2306)-Krebs, J (2331) GER email 2018 Black has decent counterplay
in this structure. A typical idea would be ...Ng6 followed by ...f6-f5.}) 6...
Nd7 $5 {[%mdl 4]} 7. d4 Ba7 8. Be2 ({An interesting idea is} 8. Nc3 {when
Black should probably start with} c6 ({In a case of} 8... Ngf6 9. g4 $5 {
is very interesting. The position is unclear. 1-0 (56) Ponkratov,P (2632)
-Adhiban,B (2654) Moscow 2019})) 8... c6 9. Nc3 Ngf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 $146
Re8 {[%cal Ga7b8,Ge5e4,Gd6d5] Now, we can see the entire point behind Black's
previous play. The position reminds the so-called Indian Defence but with a
bishop on a7, instead of e7. Black's idea is to build a kingside attack by
means of ...Bb8 followed by ...e5-e4 and ...d6-d5. The point behind freeing
the a7-square is now clear.} 12. b4 $1 {White should immediately go for active
actions.} Bb8 13. b5 e4 (13... d5 $5) 14. Nd2 d5 15. a4 Nf8 ({A decent option
would have been} 15... Nb6 $5 16. c5 Nbd7 $132 {After closing the queenside,
Black can focus on his kingside play.}) 16. Ba3 {Quite naturally, I wanted to
provoke g2-g3 that weakens the light squares. This move, however, is not the
most precise one.} Qc7 ({Better would have been} 16... Ng4 $1 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18.
g3 Be6 $132 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh3] when the weakness of the light squares will
tell in a long run.}) 17. g3 Qd7 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. cxd5 cxd5 20. Rfc1 ({
White should have played} 20. Bb5 $1 {and answer} Qh3 {with} 21. Ndxe4 $5 Rxe4
22. Nxe4 Ng4 23. f3 Nxe3 24. Qf2 Nxf1 25. Bxf1 $14 {Only White can be better
in this position. This line, however, is not easy for a human.}) 20... Qh3 21.
Bf1 Qh5 $2 (21... Qf5 $132) 22. Nb5 $4 (22. Bb5 Bd7 23. Bxf8 $1 Bxb5 (23...
Rxf8 24. Bxd7 Nxd7 25. Rab1 $18) 24. Nxb5 (24. axb5 $5) 24... Rxf8 25. Qc6 $16)
22... Ng4 23. h3 Nxf2 $1 24. Kxf2 Ra6 25. Nd6 Rxd6 26. Bxd6 Bxd6 27. Bg2 Bxh3
28. Nf1 Bxg2 29. Kxg2 Re6 30. Qd1 Qf5 31. Ra2 h5 32. Kg1 Rg6 33. Rg2 Ne6 34.
Rf2 Qg5 35. Rc8+ Kh7 36. Rh2 Rh6 37. Qe1 Qf5 38. Qxa5 Ng5 39. Qa8 Nf3+ 40. Kg2
Ne1+ 41. Kg1 Nf3+ 42. Kg2 Nxh2 43. Nxh2 Rf6 44. Rc2 Bxg3 0-1

